00:00:26.750 --> 00:00:30.740
PROFESSOR: OK, what
we're going to do,

00:00:30.740 --> 00:00:33.100
we're going to start our
story in what at the time

00:00:33.100 --> 00:00:35.590
would have been called the
Northwest United States.

00:00:35.590 --> 00:00:37.790
We're in the first
part of the 1800s,

00:00:37.790 --> 00:00:41.550
and we're really talking
about this portion of it here.

00:00:41.550 --> 00:00:43.550
Although later on in our
story, we'll actually

00:00:43.550 --> 00:00:47.340
cover this whole region here.

00:00:47.340 --> 00:00:52.360
This was a sparsely-populated,
impoverished area.

00:00:52.360 --> 00:00:54.630
There were basically
no roads or towns.

00:00:54.630 --> 00:00:57.520
There was lots of swamps,
mountains, rivers,

00:00:57.520 --> 00:01:00.300
land transportation
was very difficult.

00:01:00.300 --> 00:01:02.860
The area was more or less
under constant warfare

00:01:02.860 --> 00:01:06.040
from 1800 till about 1880.

00:01:06.040 --> 00:01:10.610
I'm talking about
large scale armies

00:01:10.610 --> 00:01:14.530
in what would be called the
Indian Wars, but also smaller

00:01:14.530 --> 00:01:18.140
scale raids of dozens
or half a dozen people,

00:01:18.140 --> 00:01:22.150
and individual murders.

00:01:22.150 --> 00:01:24.500
It was among the
poorest areas on earth.

00:01:27.910 --> 00:01:29.050
Who lived there?

00:01:29.050 --> 00:01:31.370
Anybody know?

00:01:31.370 --> 00:01:38.030
So early 1800s, 1810, 1820 in
the Northwest United States?

00:01:38.030 --> 00:01:38.989
AUDIENCE: No one?

00:01:38.989 --> 00:01:39.780
PROFESSOR: Anybody?

00:01:39.780 --> 00:01:41.090
No, people lived there.

00:01:41.090 --> 00:01:43.132
AUDIENCE: People
looking for gold?

00:01:43.132 --> 00:01:45.090
PROFESSOR: Gold miners
were a little bit later,

00:01:45.090 --> 00:01:48.254
but sure, they would come along.

00:01:48.254 --> 00:01:50.170
There were some Native
Americans, many of them

00:01:50.170 --> 00:01:52.080
had been pushed from
other places, right?

00:01:52.080 --> 00:01:55.249
The east coast Native Americans
had been pushed in there.

00:01:55.249 --> 00:01:57.040
There were some Native
Americans that lived

00:01:57.040 --> 00:02:00.010
there who were resisting that.

00:02:00.010 --> 00:02:02.648
There were also Natives being
pushed in from the South

00:02:02.648 --> 00:02:05.110
by the people in Mexico.

00:02:05.110 --> 00:02:07.870
So we've got people being in.

00:02:07.870 --> 00:02:09.539
How about Acadian Driftwood?

00:02:09.539 --> 00:02:11.280
Anybody here--?

00:02:11.280 --> 00:02:14.000
So the Canadian rebels,
who were French-speaking,

00:02:14.000 --> 00:02:16.610
are being pushed
here by the English.

00:02:16.610 --> 00:02:17.861
Whiskey Rebellion, right?

00:02:17.861 --> 00:02:19.610
The rebellious people
in the United States

00:02:19.610 --> 00:02:25.630
are being pushed out here,
escaped slaves, debtors.

00:02:25.630 --> 00:02:28.950
There is an expression
at the time, GTT.

00:02:28.950 --> 00:02:31.920
If you didn't want
to pay your debts,

00:02:31.920 --> 00:02:33.710
you wrote GTT on your door.

00:02:33.710 --> 00:02:37.200
It meant "Gone To Texas,"
and you headed over here.

00:02:37.200 --> 00:02:44.460
So we got this area full of
losers, violence, very little

00:02:44.460 --> 00:02:47.170
in the way of
economic resources.

00:02:50.314 --> 00:02:54.050
A few years ago, somebody did
a list of the 100 wealthiest

00:02:54.050 --> 00:02:54.975
Americans of all time.

00:02:54.975 --> 00:02:55.850
And they compared it.

00:02:55.850 --> 00:02:59.250
They tried to estimate
the wealth of these people

00:02:59.250 --> 00:03:01.780
and they compared it to the
total size of the economy

00:03:01.780 --> 00:03:04.190
at the time.

00:03:04.190 --> 00:03:08.850
19 of the 100 wealthiest
Americans of all time

00:03:08.850 --> 00:03:12.340
were in that Northwest
area in 1850,

00:03:12.340 --> 00:03:16.010
and they made their money
from about 1850 to 1880.

00:03:16.010 --> 00:03:17.200
So what happened?

00:03:17.200 --> 00:03:21.500
How did this poor economic
place with no prospects

00:03:21.500 --> 00:03:24.570
for anything, the last place in
the world you'd expect anybody

00:03:24.570 --> 00:03:30.360
to get rich, how did it generate
such tremendous fortunes?

00:03:30.360 --> 00:03:31.490
And it isn't just money.

00:03:31.490 --> 00:03:33.170
I mean you say, OK,
well, some of them

00:03:33.170 --> 00:03:35.731
struck gold or oil or
something like that.

00:03:35.731 --> 00:03:36.730
But listen to the names.

00:03:36.730 --> 00:03:39.775
It wasn't just robber barons
like Rockefeller, Mellon,

00:03:39.775 --> 00:03:41.420
and Carnegie.

00:03:41.420 --> 00:03:44.300
It was great inventors like
McCormick, Westinghouse,

00:03:44.300 --> 00:03:45.710
and Pullman.

00:03:45.710 --> 00:03:49.680
Innovators in other fields,
such as Swift, Pulitzer, Hearst,

00:03:49.680 --> 00:03:51.870
Armor, Marshall Field.

00:03:51.870 --> 00:03:54.810
These people are
household names today.

00:03:54.810 --> 00:03:58.390
I challenge anybody in this
room to name any other business

00:03:58.390 --> 00:04:04.900
innovator anywhere in the
world in the entire 1900s.

00:04:04.900 --> 00:04:07.610
OK, so we got 19 of them
in this little area.

00:04:07.610 --> 00:04:10.080
And we know them today, right?

00:04:10.080 --> 00:04:11.727
None anywhere else.

00:04:11.727 --> 00:04:13.560
There were some innovations
in other places,

00:04:13.560 --> 00:04:17.182
but here was clearly the
place where modern business

00:04:17.182 --> 00:04:17.890
was being formed.

00:04:17.890 --> 00:04:20.170
So what was it that they had?

00:04:20.170 --> 00:04:23.360
Was it something in the water?

00:04:23.360 --> 00:04:26.130
Something in the air?

00:04:26.130 --> 00:04:29.520
What did this region have
that nobody else had?

00:04:33.496 --> 00:04:34.490
AUDIENCE: Labor?

00:04:34.490 --> 00:04:36.410
PROFESSOR: No, it was
very sparsely populated.

00:04:36.410 --> 00:04:37.930
Labor was extremely expensive.

00:04:37.930 --> 00:04:41.930
And your laborers had to
spend most of their time

00:04:41.930 --> 00:04:45.090
eking out subsistence
living, right?

00:04:45.090 --> 00:04:48.380
It would be very expensive
to bring in food or supplies

00:04:48.380 --> 00:04:49.375
for them.

00:04:49.375 --> 00:04:52.750
No, labor was
extremely expensive.

00:04:52.750 --> 00:04:55.530
Well, I'll tell you
one thing they had was

00:04:55.530 --> 00:04:57.864
they had a game called poker.

00:04:57.864 --> 00:04:58.780
[LAUGHTER IN AUDIENCE]

00:04:58.780 --> 00:04:59.710
All right, you're laughing.

00:04:59.710 --> 00:05:01.710
I hope you won't be
laughing at the end of this.

00:05:01.710 --> 00:05:02.390
Let's go back.

00:05:02.390 --> 00:05:05.120
The first written records we
have from outside this region

00:05:05.120 --> 00:05:07.655
about poker come to us
from about the late 1820s

00:05:07.655 --> 00:05:09.719
and the early 1830s.

00:05:09.719 --> 00:05:11.260
It's a lot more
interesting what they

00:05:11.260 --> 00:05:14.510
don't say than what they say.

00:05:14.510 --> 00:05:17.690
One thing they don't say
is, people in this region

00:05:17.690 --> 00:05:20.040
played this game called poker,
and here's how it works.

00:05:20.040 --> 00:05:22.221
None of them explain
the game at all.

00:05:22.221 --> 00:05:23.470
That's kind of strange, right?

00:05:23.470 --> 00:05:24.810
Somebody comes and
tells you, hey, there's

00:05:24.810 --> 00:05:26.226
this game people
are playing here,

00:05:26.226 --> 00:05:27.790
but they don't
tell you the rules.

00:05:27.790 --> 00:05:29.910
They didn't even
describe it as a game.

00:05:29.910 --> 00:05:31.750
The one thing they
were very clear about

00:05:31.750 --> 00:05:36.300
is it involved transferring
large amounts of money.

00:05:36.300 --> 00:05:39.700
They also-- nobody said, oh,
it's a variant of this game

00:05:39.700 --> 00:05:42.550
or that game somebody
plays somewhere else.

00:05:42.550 --> 00:05:47.480
Nobody said, this is some game
you might be interested in.

00:05:47.480 --> 00:05:48.439
Everybody already knew.

00:05:48.439 --> 00:05:50.229
I mean, it was-- you
can read these things.

00:05:50.229 --> 00:05:52.310
It was common knowledge
that people in this area

00:05:52.310 --> 00:05:53.870
played a game called poker.

00:05:53.870 --> 00:05:56.780
It was a very serious game
played for very large amounts

00:05:56.780 --> 00:05:57.440
of money.

00:05:57.440 --> 00:05:59.240
It was played nowhere else.

00:05:59.240 --> 00:06:01.250
Nobody mentioned
any antecedents.

00:06:01.250 --> 00:06:04.170
Nobody said it was brought in
by the French or by the Indians

00:06:04.170 --> 00:06:08.880
or by the Persians or
by any other group.

00:06:08.880 --> 00:06:09.700
It was just there.

00:06:09.700 --> 00:06:13.144
It was there in the area.

00:06:13.144 --> 00:06:16.580
A couple other interesting
things about this game.

00:06:16.580 --> 00:06:20.695
First of all, what we know that,
far more popular than poker

00:06:20.695 --> 00:06:22.820
at any period of time, and
certainly in this period

00:06:22.820 --> 00:06:25.560
as well, were standard
gambling games

00:06:25.560 --> 00:06:27.640
that are played--
variants of which

00:06:27.640 --> 00:06:31.830
are played all over the world
by people of all classes.

00:06:31.830 --> 00:06:34.020
Dice games, faro
was very popular

00:06:34.020 --> 00:06:37.927
at the time, wheel-based
chance games.

00:06:37.927 --> 00:06:40.010
We also know though, the
other kind of game people

00:06:40.010 --> 00:06:42.790
were familiar with is played by
aristocrats-- things like whist

00:06:42.790 --> 00:06:46.170
or chess-- that don't
necessarily involve gambling,

00:06:46.170 --> 00:06:50.220
although they can, and
involve a lot of skill.

00:06:50.220 --> 00:06:53.520
Poker was neither of the above.

00:06:53.520 --> 00:06:55.490
OK, so let's start
asking, what is there

00:06:55.490 --> 00:06:57.750
about poker that was
different from any game that

00:06:57.750 --> 00:06:58.824
came before it?

00:06:58.824 --> 00:07:01.240
This might give us some clue
as to why this was different.

00:07:01.240 --> 00:07:04.050
What was going on here?

00:07:04.050 --> 00:07:06.470
Ace beats king.

00:07:06.470 --> 00:07:08.930
OK, that doesn't
seem like much today.

00:07:08.930 --> 00:07:10.930
That was pretty
revolutionary, right?

00:07:10.930 --> 00:07:13.270
You'd go to get executed in
most countries in the world

00:07:13.270 --> 00:07:15.470
in those days for saying that.

00:07:15.470 --> 00:07:18.307
And an ace was, by the
way, in early poker,

00:07:18.307 --> 00:07:19.140
ace was always high.

00:07:19.140 --> 00:07:20.520
There was no such thing
as a low/high ace.

00:07:20.520 --> 00:07:21.804
So that tells you something.

00:07:21.804 --> 00:07:23.220
OK, the people who
made this game,

00:07:23.220 --> 00:07:25.170
they weren't monarchists, right?

00:07:25.170 --> 00:07:27.382
They were thinking
a different way.

00:07:27.382 --> 00:07:28.590
Here's another thing, though.

00:07:28.590 --> 00:07:33.375
The hand rankings are
in order of rarity.

00:07:33.375 --> 00:07:35.590
The rarer the hand,
the higher it ranks.

00:07:35.590 --> 00:07:39.940
And in early poker, we didn't
have straights and flushes,

00:07:39.940 --> 00:07:42.142
so it's even more
straightforward.

00:07:42.142 --> 00:07:43.850
But here's something
kind of interesting.

00:07:43.850 --> 00:07:45.599
Here's something that
changed in the game.

00:07:45.599 --> 00:07:49.520
So in the early poker up
until about the 1830s,

00:07:49.520 --> 00:07:51.150
this principle that
the rarer the hand,

00:07:51.150 --> 00:07:53.940
the more valuable it was was
actually employed much more

00:07:53.940 --> 00:07:55.440
consistently.

00:07:55.440 --> 00:07:58.100
So today when you
compare two hands that

00:07:58.100 --> 00:08:00.520
are of the same
time-- so two people

00:08:00.520 --> 00:08:02.010
each have two pair,
two people each

00:08:02.010 --> 00:08:05.950
have a pair, two people
each have a nothing hand.

00:08:05.950 --> 00:08:09.915
You decide the winner starting
from the highest cards on down.

00:08:09.915 --> 00:08:12.040
Right, so if I have two
pair and you have two pair,

00:08:12.040 --> 00:08:14.522
we first look at who has
the higher highest pair.

00:08:14.522 --> 00:08:16.230
Then we look at who
has the higher lowest

00:08:16.230 --> 00:08:18.500
pair if that's a tie.

00:08:18.500 --> 00:08:21.610
But in early poker,
it was reversed.

00:08:21.610 --> 00:08:24.830
And you can see if you rank
it the way we do today,

00:08:24.830 --> 00:08:26.300
we've inverted our principle.

00:08:26.300 --> 00:08:29.730
Now, the more common the
hand-- like ace high hands,

00:08:29.730 --> 00:08:32.424
there are 500,000 out
of the 1.3 million.

00:08:32.424 --> 00:08:34.590
These are hands with no
straight, no flush, no pair,

00:08:34.590 --> 00:08:36.495
no match.

00:08:36.495 --> 00:08:38.120
The ace high hands
are the most common,

00:08:38.120 --> 00:08:40.470
but they rank the highest.

00:08:40.470 --> 00:08:43.527
In poker up till about,
like I say, the 1830s,

00:08:43.527 --> 00:08:45.360
we ranked it by the
lowest card in the hand.

00:08:45.360 --> 00:08:47.193
So you first compared
your lowest card, then

00:08:47.193 --> 00:08:48.320
your second lowest.

00:08:48.320 --> 00:08:51.620
And there you see we are
true to the principle

00:08:51.620 --> 00:08:55.590
that the rarer the hand,
the higher it ranks.

00:08:55.590 --> 00:08:58.030
Can anybody see the strategic
difference this makes?

00:08:58.030 --> 00:08:59.690
Why is this important?

00:08:59.690 --> 00:09:02.872
Is it just completely arbitrary?

00:09:02.872 --> 00:09:04.080
What difference does it make?

00:09:04.080 --> 00:09:06.340
Let's say we did things
this way in poker.

00:09:06.340 --> 00:09:09.550
What difference would
it make to the play?

00:09:09.550 --> 00:09:13.460
What it means is aces
are much less valuable.

00:09:13.460 --> 00:09:17.090
It's a lot like-- anybody
here every play lowball poker?

00:09:17.090 --> 00:09:20.250
Lowball poker, your best
cards don't help you.

00:09:20.250 --> 00:09:22.434
The question is,
what's your worst card?

00:09:22.434 --> 00:09:23.850
You talk about a
lowball hand, you

00:09:23.850 --> 00:09:25.800
talk about the highest card
in my hand that makes it.

00:09:25.800 --> 00:09:27.990
You can have four great
cards, and a fifth card

00:09:27.990 --> 00:09:28.980
can completely ruin it.

00:09:28.980 --> 00:09:31.610
You can ace, king, queen,
jack and then a two,

00:09:31.610 --> 00:09:35.920
and you've got a two low hand,
and you lose to everybody else.

00:09:35.920 --> 00:09:38.757
In the modern poker,
if you have an ace--

00:09:38.757 --> 00:09:40.840
let's say we both have
hands and neither one of us

00:09:40.840 --> 00:09:43.790
has any matches or
straight or flush.

00:09:43.790 --> 00:09:48.830
If I have an ace, I have an
83% chance that I beat you.

00:09:48.830 --> 00:09:51.500
But if we rank them
by low card, an ace

00:09:51.500 --> 00:09:53.770
only gives you a 56%
chance of winning.

00:09:53.770 --> 00:09:56.854
An ace is much less valuable
because really the difference

00:09:56.854 --> 00:09:58.270
between ace, king,
queen, and jack

00:09:58.270 --> 00:10:00.436
is very little, because
it's your lowest card that's

00:10:00.436 --> 00:10:03.911
going to determine how
strong your hand is.

00:10:03.911 --> 00:10:05.910
Now, the biggest point I
want to make about this

00:10:05.910 --> 00:10:08.920
isn't the subtleties
of a strategy

00:10:08.920 --> 00:10:11.050
when you rank hands this way.

00:10:11.050 --> 00:10:13.374
This is a game
that was designed.

00:10:13.374 --> 00:10:15.665
This is a game that somebody
thought about, articulated

00:10:15.665 --> 00:10:19.710
a rational principle, and
did what was at the time

00:10:19.710 --> 00:10:24.390
some pretty clever mathematics
to figure out the ranking.

00:10:24.390 --> 00:10:27.500
This is not a game that
evolved by long tradition.

00:10:27.500 --> 00:10:29.660
This is not a game where
somebody in a court

00:10:29.660 --> 00:10:31.177
sat down and wrote the rules.

00:10:31.177 --> 00:10:32.760
This is a game that
somebody designed,

00:10:32.760 --> 00:10:36.200
and they designed
it for a reason.

00:10:36.200 --> 00:10:37.840
But actually, the
card playing poker

00:10:37.840 --> 00:10:40.940
is pretty trivially simple,
and especially straight poker.

00:10:40.940 --> 00:10:43.500
It was called straight
poker at the time.

00:10:43.500 --> 00:10:47.930
The way the game was played
was you were dealt a card,

00:10:47.930 --> 00:10:50.540
you had a betting round, you
were dealt a second card,

00:10:50.540 --> 00:10:51.720
you had a betting around.

00:10:51.720 --> 00:10:54.090
You were dealt a third card,
you had a betting round,

00:10:54.090 --> 00:10:55.866
and then that was
the last round.

00:10:55.866 --> 00:10:57.240
The last two
cards-- at the time,

00:10:57.240 --> 00:10:58.906
they were called the
turn and the river,

00:10:58.906 --> 00:11:01.920
just like in hold 'em
today-- were dealt together,

00:11:01.920 --> 00:11:04.590
and there was no betting
after the final card.

00:11:04.590 --> 00:11:07.121
I'll tell you why that's
important in a bit.

00:11:07.121 --> 00:11:09.120
Another thing about the
way the betting was done

00:11:09.120 --> 00:11:11.700
is there was no ante.

00:11:11.700 --> 00:11:14.910
There was no blind in the
sense we know it today.

00:11:14.910 --> 00:11:17.390
The way the betting
worked-- and again, this

00:11:17.390 --> 00:11:19.890
shows some very careful
design on somebody's part--

00:11:19.890 --> 00:11:21.950
the dealer dealt the cards.

00:11:21.950 --> 00:11:26.140
The person to the dealer's
left was known as the age.

00:11:26.140 --> 00:11:28.590
The age posted a
stake, and they could

00:11:28.590 --> 00:11:31.410
post any, before they saw
their card, their first card.

00:11:31.410 --> 00:11:33.460
They could post a stake,
any amount they wanted,

00:11:33.460 --> 00:11:34.510
including zero.

00:11:34.510 --> 00:11:36.947
They didn't have
to post anything.

00:11:36.947 --> 00:11:38.530
But the rules were
a little different.

00:11:38.530 --> 00:11:40.650
On the first-- and this is
only on the first round.

00:11:40.650 --> 00:11:42.233
All the subsequent
rounds, the betting

00:11:42.233 --> 00:11:44.400
is exactly the same
as modern poker.

00:11:44.400 --> 00:11:46.980
But on the first
round, you were not

00:11:46.980 --> 00:11:48.900
allowed to call the age's bet.

00:11:48.900 --> 00:11:51.360
So let's say the age bets $1.

00:11:51.360 --> 00:11:52.300
You cannot call that.

00:11:52.300 --> 00:11:54.455
You can fold, or you can raise.

00:11:54.455 --> 00:11:57.350
And the minimum raises the
amount to the minimum bet

00:11:57.350 --> 00:11:59.290
would be $2.

00:11:59.290 --> 00:12:01.940
So this gives a
lot more advantage

00:12:01.940 --> 00:12:04.410
to the age compared
to somebody who

00:12:04.410 --> 00:12:08.070
posts a blind today, a
blind that can be called.

00:12:08.070 --> 00:12:09.609
In a way, you can
see the analogy

00:12:09.609 --> 00:12:11.900
between what the age does
and what the small blind does

00:12:11.900 --> 00:12:15.690
in poker, that somebody has
to double the bet in order

00:12:15.690 --> 00:12:16.190
to play.

00:12:16.190 --> 00:12:19.430
Although in modern poker, with
a small blind and a big blind,

00:12:19.430 --> 00:12:22.930
someone is forced to
come in and double.

00:12:22.930 --> 00:12:25.210
The poker players at the
time were very insistent.

00:12:25.210 --> 00:12:27.850
They said poker is not gambling.

00:12:27.850 --> 00:12:29.730
And the difference
between poker and gambling

00:12:29.730 --> 00:12:34.380
is no one is ever
forced to make a bet.

00:12:34.380 --> 00:12:36.435
You look at your
cards, you voluntarily

00:12:36.435 --> 00:12:38.310
make a bet that you
think has-- they wouldn't

00:12:38.310 --> 00:12:40.226
use the word at the time,
but we would say now

00:12:40.226 --> 00:12:43.350
is that you think has
positive expected value.

00:12:43.350 --> 00:12:46.150
The first, the blind
bet, was empirically

00:12:46.150 --> 00:12:47.570
known to be a winning.

00:12:47.570 --> 00:12:50.060
It was an advantage
people posted.

00:12:50.060 --> 00:12:52.510
Now mathematically, you can
show that can't be true.

00:12:52.510 --> 00:12:54.590
But psychologically
and empirically,

00:12:54.590 --> 00:12:57.260
it was true, that posting the
blind with other people being

00:12:57.260 --> 00:13:02.560
forced to either double or fold
was empirically an advantage.

00:13:02.560 --> 00:13:04.220
Anyone else betting,
they could bet

00:13:04.220 --> 00:13:05.520
if they thought they would win.

00:13:05.520 --> 00:13:07.925
They didn't have to
bet if they didn't.

00:13:11.980 --> 00:13:14.629
So let's talk about
the betting in poker.

00:13:14.629 --> 00:13:16.170
There are a couple
of things about it

00:13:16.170 --> 00:13:19.460
that are different from any
other game that comes before.

00:13:19.460 --> 00:13:21.960
The first one is that at the
end of every betting round,

00:13:21.960 --> 00:13:26.150
everyone remaining in the hand
has bet exactly the same amount

00:13:26.150 --> 00:13:27.910
of money.

00:13:27.910 --> 00:13:30.690
The hand is mark-to-market
after every round.

00:13:30.690 --> 00:13:32.320
So ultimately,
you're betting on who

00:13:32.320 --> 00:13:34.019
has the best hand
at showdown, or who

00:13:34.019 --> 00:13:36.060
has the best surviving
hand at showdown of people

00:13:36.060 --> 00:13:37.570
who haven't folded.

00:13:37.570 --> 00:13:40.070
But in between the way,
at the end of every round,

00:13:40.070 --> 00:13:43.800
the game cannot continue until
everyone remaining in the hand

00:13:43.800 --> 00:13:44.915
has bet the same amount.

00:13:50.430 --> 00:13:52.770
This didn't last all that long.

00:13:52.770 --> 00:13:56.040
So by the 1840s,
1850s, we're saying

00:13:56.040 --> 00:14:01.950
there's a lot of fight against
these very strict rules.

00:14:01.950 --> 00:14:06.440
People started adding antes.

00:14:06.440 --> 00:14:09.160
People started adding
straights and flushes.

00:14:09.160 --> 00:14:15.300
People started adding betting
after the final round of cards.

00:14:15.300 --> 00:14:18.280
People started adding all kinds
of more complicated games--

00:14:18.280 --> 00:14:23.390
draw poker, stud poker
with some cards revealed.

00:14:23.390 --> 00:14:25.870
They started adding
new kinds of hands.

00:14:25.870 --> 00:14:28.610
So the game starts to
change a little bit.

00:14:28.610 --> 00:14:32.615
And R.F. Foster,
who was probably

00:14:32.615 --> 00:14:34.240
one of the first
people to really write

00:14:34.240 --> 00:14:35.660
a comprehensive
history of poker--

00:14:35.660 --> 00:14:38.820
and this was 100
years later, really--

00:14:38.820 --> 00:14:39.820
explained what happened.

00:14:39.820 --> 00:14:43.080
So there is this
conservative, old game,

00:14:43.080 --> 00:14:46.290
scientific based on
very rigid principles,

00:14:46.290 --> 00:14:48.400
that eventually evolved
into the modern game.

00:14:48.400 --> 00:14:50.290
The modern game, a
lot more fun to play.

00:14:50.290 --> 00:14:54.890
The modern game allows
gambling, clearly.

00:14:54.890 --> 00:14:59.410
The modern game is really for
a somewhat different purpose.

00:14:59.410 --> 00:15:01.080
But so far, we've
talked about the cards

00:15:01.080 --> 00:15:03.180
and we've talked
about the betting.

00:15:03.180 --> 00:15:05.820
We actually haven't talked about
the most revolutionary thing

00:15:05.820 --> 00:15:08.710
in poker that, again, is like no
other game that came before it.

00:15:12.480 --> 00:15:15.060
Most gambling games throughout
history-- and remember,

00:15:15.060 --> 00:15:16.890
gambling goes back
to human prehistory.

00:15:16.890 --> 00:15:20.610
Virtually every culture
has forms of gambling.

00:15:20.610 --> 00:15:24.840
But gambling is almost always
done for either goods or cash.

00:15:24.840 --> 00:15:29.840
When credit was used, credit
was provided by a trusted

00:15:29.840 --> 00:15:30.780
central counterparty.

00:15:30.780 --> 00:15:33.350
So somebody who organized the
game might organize credit.

00:15:36.200 --> 00:15:39.330
Poker was never played for
cash, never played for goods.

00:15:39.330 --> 00:15:41.720
Poker was played
for what were called

00:15:41.720 --> 00:15:43.577
at the time "poker checks."

00:15:43.577 --> 00:15:45.660
And this is a distinction
that goes all the way up

00:15:45.660 --> 00:15:50.830
to about the 1980s before
it finally got erased.

00:15:50.830 --> 00:15:56.270
Even as late as the 1980s
when I was playing poker,

00:15:56.270 --> 00:15:58.720
there was a distinction,
and people understood it.

00:15:58.720 --> 00:16:02.090
There were two similar things
that were often confused.

00:16:02.090 --> 00:16:04.930
There were checks,
and there were chips.

00:16:04.930 --> 00:16:06.912
And they looked kind of similar.

00:16:06.912 --> 00:16:11.150
A check had intrinsic value.

00:16:11.150 --> 00:16:12.440
Checks were used for cash.

00:16:12.440 --> 00:16:14.370
Casino checks were used
for cash in Las Vegas.

00:16:14.370 --> 00:16:15.320
Nobody ever used cash.

00:16:15.320 --> 00:16:20.260
You just used casino chips
for all your transactions.

00:16:20.260 --> 00:16:24.290
But they were also used for
all different kinds of games.

00:16:24.290 --> 00:16:26.450
Chips are just markers.

00:16:26.450 --> 00:16:28.670
Chips are things you
buy at the table,

00:16:28.670 --> 00:16:31.310
and you're supposed to cash them
in when you leave the table.

00:16:31.310 --> 00:16:34.750
You're not even supposed to take
them from the roulette table

00:16:34.750 --> 00:16:37.217
over to the craps table
or something like that.

00:16:37.217 --> 00:16:38.300
So chips are just markers.

00:16:38.300 --> 00:16:41.580
They have no intrinsic value.

00:16:41.580 --> 00:16:43.037
There is a complicated
story which

00:16:43.037 --> 00:16:45.120
I'd be happy to talk to
you people about sometime.

00:16:45.120 --> 00:16:46.330
The IRS came down.

00:16:46.330 --> 00:16:51.050
And some casinos, when they
pushed organized crime out,

00:16:51.050 --> 00:16:52.620
they got rid of checks.

00:16:52.620 --> 00:16:57.290
So right now, there's no such
thing as, a least a legal,

00:16:57.290 --> 00:16:59.830
chip with a real,
intrinsic value.

00:16:59.830 --> 00:17:01.040
They're just markers.

00:17:01.040 --> 00:17:04.381
If you show up to a
casino with a $5,000 chip

00:17:04.381 --> 00:17:05.839
and you want to
cash it in, they're

00:17:05.839 --> 00:17:07.470
going to ask you
where you got it,

00:17:07.470 --> 00:17:10.680
prove that you bought it at a
Casino or won it at a casino.

00:17:10.680 --> 00:17:13.400
If you can't, they won't
give you any money for it.

00:17:16.579 --> 00:17:19.750
But let's go back
to the early 1800s.

00:17:19.750 --> 00:17:21.790
The way poker was played
was with poker checks.

00:17:21.790 --> 00:17:24.349
Poker checks were markers.

00:17:24.349 --> 00:17:26.040
Often, they were
made out of clay.

00:17:26.040 --> 00:17:27.930
People would make little
disks out of clay,

00:17:27.930 --> 00:17:29.370
and they would put
a thumb print in it.

00:17:29.370 --> 00:17:31.036
They would put some
identifiable marker.

00:17:31.036 --> 00:17:36.630
The key thing is that they were
identifiable to an individual.

00:17:36.630 --> 00:17:40.190
You were playing poker with
money you created yourself.

00:17:40.190 --> 00:17:42.570
And if you lost, other people
would have these markers,

00:17:42.570 --> 00:17:45.470
and these markers
would be claims on you.

00:17:45.470 --> 00:17:49.110
If you won, you had
other people's markers.

00:17:49.110 --> 00:17:50.700
At the end of the
game, people did

00:17:50.700 --> 00:17:53.421
something called ring
clearing, which means, oh, OK.

00:17:53.421 --> 00:17:54.670
You played a game for a while.

00:17:54.670 --> 00:17:56.410
You've got a bunch of
checks in front of you.

00:17:56.410 --> 00:17:58.868
You're going to take the checks
you have from other people,

00:17:58.868 --> 00:18:01.477
you're going to trade them
for your own checks back.

00:18:01.477 --> 00:18:03.560
You're going to end up
with, if you were a winner,

00:18:03.560 --> 00:18:06.101
you're going to end up with a
bunch of other people's checks,

00:18:06.101 --> 00:18:08.050
and suddenly a bunch of
people owe you money.

00:18:08.050 --> 00:18:10.520
Or if you were a
loser, other people

00:18:10.520 --> 00:18:12.030
are going to end up with yours.

00:18:12.030 --> 00:18:13.405
But it's a winners
responsibility

00:18:13.405 --> 00:18:14.600
to collect from the losers.

00:18:14.600 --> 00:18:15.933
There's no central counterparty.

00:18:15.933 --> 00:18:17.460
There's no trusting.

00:18:17.460 --> 00:18:18.460
You play.

00:18:18.460 --> 00:18:20.494
If you don't like a
guy's checks, too bad.

00:18:20.494 --> 00:18:22.660
You got some things that
aren't-- maybe you can find

00:18:22.660 --> 00:18:25.589
somebody else to trade
you something for them.

00:18:25.589 --> 00:18:27.880
Now what you've done is you've
created a form of money.

00:18:27.880 --> 00:18:31.350
It's this credit creation that
is a really essential element

00:18:31.350 --> 00:18:33.437
of early poker.

00:18:33.437 --> 00:18:35.520
And let's talk about another
financial institution

00:18:35.520 --> 00:18:38.170
from this period-- the
soft money bank, otherwise

00:18:38.170 --> 00:18:40.630
called a wildcat bank.

00:18:40.630 --> 00:18:42.090
People created banks.

00:18:42.090 --> 00:18:44.090
And the way they created
banks is somebody said,

00:18:44.090 --> 00:18:48.329
I have a bank, and I'm
going to make loans.

00:18:48.329 --> 00:18:50.620
And I'll either print up some
bank notes, some of which

00:18:50.620 --> 00:18:52.520
were extremely crude.

00:18:52.520 --> 00:18:55.932
People even used markers,
twigs, old tally sticks,

00:18:55.932 --> 00:18:56.640
things like that.

00:18:56.640 --> 00:19:00.640
They used anything they
could find as bank notes.

00:19:00.640 --> 00:19:03.270
Or they just kept an
accounting system.

00:19:03.270 --> 00:19:05.920
If you want to spend
the money, somebody

00:19:05.920 --> 00:19:09.020
has to deposit it into the bank.

00:19:09.020 --> 00:19:12.777
If it worked, this generated
a lot of economic activity.

00:19:12.777 --> 00:19:13.860
Everything was successful.

00:19:13.860 --> 00:19:15.090
The loans paid off.

00:19:15.090 --> 00:19:16.047
Deposits were honored.

00:19:16.047 --> 00:19:16.880
Everything was fine.

00:19:16.880 --> 00:19:21.530
If it didn't work,
everything was worthless.

00:19:21.530 --> 00:19:23.520
If you add one
feature to this, it

00:19:23.520 --> 00:19:25.270
comes what most people
think of as a bank.

00:19:25.270 --> 00:19:28.860
The one feature we're missing
from this bank is what?

00:19:28.860 --> 00:19:29.890
Actual money, gold.

00:19:29.890 --> 00:19:30.720
Right.

00:19:30.720 --> 00:19:32.750
Now, this is kind of an
interesting dichotomy

00:19:32.750 --> 00:19:34.220
in economics.

00:19:34.220 --> 00:19:39.320
To me, a classic bank
is a soft money back.

00:19:39.320 --> 00:19:42.650
Capital, to me, is an
additional feature that gives it

00:19:42.650 --> 00:19:44.070
some credibility, right?

00:19:44.070 --> 00:19:45.270
It means two things.

00:19:45.270 --> 00:19:46.920
It means the person
creating the bank

00:19:46.920 --> 00:19:48.390
is going to have some
skin in the game,

00:19:48.390 --> 00:19:50.973
is going to take a loss if the
whole bank collapses, if nobody

00:19:50.973 --> 00:19:52.370
ever pays back their loans.

00:19:52.370 --> 00:19:55.530
So that shows-- it's a signal to
show they have some confidence.

00:19:55.530 --> 00:19:59.700
Also, the cash they put in, the
capital they put in, in theory

00:19:59.700 --> 00:20:03.602
is going to help people
if the bank fails.

00:20:03.602 --> 00:20:05.310
It'll pay off some
portion of the losses.

00:20:05.310 --> 00:20:06.410
In practice, it never does.

00:20:06.410 --> 00:20:08.409
In practice, the people
who run the banks always

00:20:08.409 --> 00:20:12.360
get their capital out
before anybody else.

00:20:12.360 --> 00:20:14.880
But a lot of the legislation
on banks, a lot of the way

00:20:14.880 --> 00:20:17.250
people think about
banks, is the opposite.

00:20:17.250 --> 00:20:19.960
They think about it as a
classic bank is something

00:20:19.960 --> 00:20:22.930
that has 100% capital, and
that fractional reserve

00:20:22.930 --> 00:20:28.940
is some kind of like little
extra thing you do to a bank.

00:20:28.940 --> 00:20:31.550
But we see, if you look again,
human prehistory cultures,

00:20:31.550 --> 00:20:35.400
you see almost all cultures have
some form of this self credit

00:20:35.400 --> 00:20:41.480
equation, all kinds of things--
susus, tontines, [INAUDIBLE].

00:20:41.480 --> 00:20:43.650
All over the world, we
have these kinds of things,

00:20:43.650 --> 00:20:46.240
and they were useful
in the American West.

00:20:46.240 --> 00:20:47.729
Well, poker was one of them.

00:20:47.729 --> 00:20:49.770
Poker was a way you could
create a form of money,

00:20:49.770 --> 00:20:50.600
your own money.

00:20:50.600 --> 00:20:52.230
You could play a game.

00:20:52.230 --> 00:20:55.940
If you won, you picked up a lot
of credit from other people,

00:20:55.940 --> 00:20:57.365
and you could use
that to generate

00:20:57.365 --> 00:20:59.005
some economic activity.

00:20:59.005 --> 00:21:01.792
If you lost, other people
had to employ you, right?

00:21:01.792 --> 00:21:03.500
They had to get their
money back somehow.

00:21:03.500 --> 00:21:04.599
You didn't have any money.

00:21:04.599 --> 00:21:06.140
They had to find
things for you to do

00:21:06.140 --> 00:21:08.380
to work in their businesses.

00:21:08.380 --> 00:21:10.869
And this is how
a lot of business

00:21:10.869 --> 00:21:12.035
was created in the old west.

00:21:14.580 --> 00:21:18.680
Now we're going to move a little
forward to around the 1840s.

00:21:18.680 --> 00:21:20.490
Anyone know what this is?

00:21:20.490 --> 00:21:22.990
It is the Chicago
Board of Trade.

00:21:22.990 --> 00:21:25.960
This is actually around 1900,
so it wouldn't be quite so fancy

00:21:25.960 --> 00:21:29.320
back in 1840.

00:21:29.320 --> 00:21:33.290
Futures exchanges,
again, appeared

00:21:33.290 --> 00:21:37.750
in exactly the same geographic
area as the game of poker

00:21:37.750 --> 00:21:40.850
about 20 years later.

00:21:40.850 --> 00:21:42.530
Nobody invented it.

00:21:42.530 --> 00:21:45.116
Suddenly, these things started
popping up all over the place.

00:21:45.116 --> 00:21:46.740
A financial institution
no one had ever

00:21:46.740 --> 00:21:50.000
seen before, completely
unlike anything in the past,

00:21:50.000 --> 00:21:53.815
none of them outside the region,
ubiquitous inside the region,

00:21:53.815 --> 00:21:55.190
and nobody said
they invented it.

00:21:55.190 --> 00:21:57.390
There was something
in the culture,

00:21:57.390 --> 00:22:00.070
in the way people thought, the
way people did business that

00:22:00.070 --> 00:22:02.670
made this a very
natural thing to do,

00:22:02.670 --> 00:22:05.280
even though it had
never been done before.

00:22:05.280 --> 00:22:09.130
And the analogies with poker
are pretty obvious, right?

00:22:09.130 --> 00:22:10.940
Mark-to-market.

00:22:10.940 --> 00:22:14.310
Every day, you're betting on the
price of wheat in three months,

00:22:14.310 --> 00:22:17.120
but every day you settle up so
that you got the same amount

00:22:17.120 --> 00:22:18.750
of money at stake.

00:22:18.750 --> 00:22:21.730
Clearing-- again, the initial
exchanges in the early days,

00:22:21.730 --> 00:22:24.360
they used ring clearing,
exactly the same as poker.

00:22:24.360 --> 00:22:26.340
Later on, they went to
a full clearinghouse

00:22:26.340 --> 00:22:28.760
that was a little
more sophisticated

00:22:28.760 --> 00:22:31.900
and allowed people to do it.

00:22:31.900 --> 00:22:33.650
But what's the purpose
of these exchanges?

00:22:33.650 --> 00:22:36.396
What does this futures
exchange do for people?

00:22:36.396 --> 00:22:37.987
AUDIENCE: To lock in the price.

00:22:37.987 --> 00:22:38.820
PROFESSOR: Like who?

00:22:38.820 --> 00:22:39.650
Who would want to
lock in a price?

00:22:39.650 --> 00:22:40.596
AUDIENCE: The farmers.

00:22:40.596 --> 00:22:40.940
PROFESSOR: OK.

00:22:40.940 --> 00:22:42.148
Well, let's think about this.

00:22:42.148 --> 00:22:45.470
I'm a farmer in 1840.

00:22:45.470 --> 00:22:49.440
I'm about a two-week journey
from Chicago over bad roads.

00:22:49.440 --> 00:22:51.940
Normally, I do what farmers
have done since the beginning

00:22:51.940 --> 00:22:56.440
of private agriculture.

00:22:56.440 --> 00:22:57.940
They would sell to a crop buyer.

00:22:57.940 --> 00:22:59.940
I would go to the place
where I buy my supplies,

00:22:59.940 --> 00:23:02.440
and there's a crop buyer
who has an agent there,

00:23:02.440 --> 00:23:06.191
or that agent also comes by
my farm every month or so

00:23:06.191 --> 00:23:08.440
to check out how the crops
are going, because he wants

00:23:08.440 --> 00:23:09.570
to keep tabs on the crops.

00:23:09.570 --> 00:23:12.020
And also, I can lock
in a price with him.

00:23:12.020 --> 00:23:15.037
He will buy exactly my crop.

00:23:15.037 --> 00:23:17.120
He will buy whatever
quantity I happen to produce.

00:23:17.120 --> 00:23:19.494
He'll agree on a price now,
or he'll set the price later.

00:23:19.494 --> 00:23:21.090
Whatever I want.

00:23:21.090 --> 00:23:21.730
I deliver it.

00:23:21.730 --> 00:23:24.280
I can deliver it to him, or
for a slightly lower price,

00:23:24.280 --> 00:23:27.184
he'll come and pick
it up at my farm.

00:23:27.184 --> 00:23:28.850
Now let's compare
that with this futures

00:23:28.850 --> 00:23:30.490
exchange, a brand
new innovation that's

00:23:30.490 --> 00:23:32.590
going to make my life better.

00:23:32.590 --> 00:23:35.340
I can take a two-week
journey into Chicago.

00:23:35.340 --> 00:23:37.820
I can promise to
delivery set quantity

00:23:37.820 --> 00:23:40.720
of a set grade of wheat that
I don't produce that I can't

00:23:40.720 --> 00:23:42.742
be sure I will have on time.

00:23:42.742 --> 00:23:44.700
I don't know the quantity
I'm going to produce,

00:23:44.700 --> 00:23:46.924
but I have to specify that.

00:23:46.924 --> 00:23:48.340
I have to put down
initial margin.

00:23:48.340 --> 00:23:49.260
I don't have any cash.

00:23:49.260 --> 00:23:50.860
All my cash is
tied up in my crop.

00:23:50.860 --> 00:23:54.785
Farmers only have
cash after harvest.

00:23:54.785 --> 00:23:56.410
And I have to stay
in Chicago every day

00:23:56.410 --> 00:23:59.860
to make mark-to-market payments,
since who's growing my wheat?

00:23:59.860 --> 00:24:01.924
OK, so this makes
absolutely no sense.

00:24:01.924 --> 00:24:03.340
Anytime you read
a textbook and it

00:24:03.340 --> 00:24:05.700
talks about farmers
using futures exchanges,

00:24:05.700 --> 00:24:08.887
you know they haven't spent half
a second thinking about this.

00:24:08.887 --> 00:24:10.720
There were no farmers
involved in setting up

00:24:10.720 --> 00:24:12.140
the futures exchanges.

00:24:12.140 --> 00:24:14.570
In fact, farmers were
suspicious and have often

00:24:14.570 --> 00:24:16.510
tried to have them shut down.

00:24:16.510 --> 00:24:18.880
When farmers do use
futures exchanges,

00:24:18.880 --> 00:24:21.190
they almost always
buy the product.

00:24:21.190 --> 00:24:23.750
They don't sell it.

00:24:23.750 --> 00:24:26.340
So let's talk about what people
really use these things for.

00:24:26.340 --> 00:24:29.440
Here is the canonical
trade that you

00:24:29.440 --> 00:24:33.470
can think about, what you want
to understand futures markets.

00:24:33.470 --> 00:24:34.820
I'm a processor.

00:24:34.820 --> 00:24:36.530
All the people who
set these things up--

00:24:36.530 --> 00:24:38.780
and by the why, all the
people who set these things up

00:24:38.780 --> 00:24:39.930
were poker players.

00:24:39.930 --> 00:24:40.724
I'm not kidding.

00:24:40.724 --> 00:24:42.140
Look it up, you
find the name, you

00:24:42.140 --> 00:24:43.848
find all these people
were poker players.

00:24:46.170 --> 00:24:49.047
I grind wheat, OK?

00:24:49.047 --> 00:24:50.630
I'm not going to use
this for hedging.

00:24:50.630 --> 00:24:53.350
I can't use it for
hedging, right?

00:24:53.350 --> 00:24:55.660
I buy wheat, that's true.

00:24:55.660 --> 00:24:58.230
But is my exposure to
wheat going up in price

00:24:58.230 --> 00:25:00.830
or going down in price?

00:25:00.830 --> 00:25:02.017
One going up.

00:25:02.017 --> 00:25:03.350
OK, let me tell you two stories.

00:25:03.350 --> 00:25:06.317
Story number one,
there's a sudden increase

00:25:06.317 --> 00:25:07.150
in demand for wheat.

00:25:07.150 --> 00:25:10.380
There's a big war in
Europe, other crops

00:25:10.380 --> 00:25:11.780
fail in other regions.

00:25:11.780 --> 00:25:13.769
The price of wheat goes way up.

00:25:13.769 --> 00:25:14.935
What happens to my business?

00:25:18.107 --> 00:25:19.440
I'm making lots of money, right?

00:25:19.440 --> 00:25:20.780
They've got to
grind lots of wheat.

00:25:20.780 --> 00:25:22.260
They're bringing all the wheat
in from all the [INAUDIBLE].

00:25:22.260 --> 00:25:24.580
Everybody grinds it, there's a
shortage of grinding capacity,

00:25:24.580 --> 00:25:25.450
I can raise my prices.

00:25:25.450 --> 00:25:25.950
I'm rich.

00:25:25.950 --> 00:25:27.540
So it that way, I'm
long wheat, right?

00:25:27.540 --> 00:25:31.220
Price of wheat goes up,
my business goes up.

00:25:31.220 --> 00:25:32.230
Let's say-- sorry?

00:25:32.230 --> 00:25:34.140
AUDIENCE: So you're
assuming that the price

00:25:34.140 --> 00:25:37.260
of grounded wheat is directly
correlated to the price

00:25:37.260 --> 00:25:37.760
of wheat?

00:25:37.760 --> 00:25:38.460
PROFESSOR: Yes.

00:25:38.460 --> 00:25:41.530
I'm saying the price of
ground wheat is what went up.

00:25:41.530 --> 00:25:43.810
And because the price
of ground wheat went up,

00:25:43.810 --> 00:25:45.450
my business is more valuable.

00:25:45.450 --> 00:25:47.960
And you're exactly-- you
hit the point exactly,

00:25:47.960 --> 00:25:49.580
if that's the stuff I'm selling.

00:25:49.580 --> 00:25:51.240
Now let's do a different story.

00:25:51.240 --> 00:25:53.184
There's a crop
failure in the area.

00:25:53.184 --> 00:25:54.600
Price of wheat
goes way up, right?

00:25:54.600 --> 00:25:56.060
Wheat is scarce.

00:25:56.060 --> 00:25:57.460
Who wants my
grinding facilities?

00:25:57.460 --> 00:25:58.020
Nobody.

00:25:58.020 --> 00:25:59.728
There's an excess of
grinding facilities.

00:25:59.728 --> 00:26:01.220
I can't charge a penny.

00:26:01.220 --> 00:26:04.160
OK, so I have no
natural wheat exposure.

00:26:04.160 --> 00:26:07.380
I can't hedge my wheat exposure
in this futures market.

00:26:07.380 --> 00:26:09.620
Also, for the same reasons
I mentioned of a farmer,

00:26:09.620 --> 00:26:11.630
it's not a convenient
place to do it.

00:26:11.630 --> 00:26:13.660
It's a type and grade
of wheat I don't

00:26:13.660 --> 00:26:17.370
want at a place I don't want.

00:26:17.370 --> 00:26:19.620
Also, the price of
wheat has very little

00:26:19.620 --> 00:26:20.740
do with my business.

00:26:20.740 --> 00:26:25.795
What I care about is my
machinery operating properly,

00:26:25.795 --> 00:26:28.170
what's the price of fuel,
what's the price of labor, what

00:26:28.170 --> 00:26:29.836
are the regulations
on the stuff, what's

00:26:29.836 --> 00:26:31.800
the equality of the
stuff I'm getting.

00:26:31.800 --> 00:26:35.440
I can lock in prices with
suppliers and either buyers

00:26:35.440 --> 00:26:39.100
or the flour or sellers of
the wheat anytime I want.

00:26:39.100 --> 00:26:41.820
That's not the point
of the futures market.

00:26:41.820 --> 00:26:44.435
What you want to think
about is I'm growing wheat.

00:26:44.435 --> 00:26:46.240
I'm going to go to a
silo, a grain silo.

00:26:46.240 --> 00:26:48.870
A grain silo is a guy, he buys
wheat from all over the place

00:26:48.870 --> 00:26:51.024
and he sells it
to people like me.

00:26:51.024 --> 00:26:52.690
I'm going to say, OK,
I want these wheat

00:26:52.690 --> 00:26:55.360
deliveries over the
next three months,

00:26:55.360 --> 00:26:58.250
so much and so on
these various times.

00:26:58.250 --> 00:27:01.980
I want it delivered to
my grinding facility.

00:27:01.980 --> 00:27:06.660
I want exactly this
type and kind of wheat.

00:27:06.660 --> 00:27:09.810
And he'll agree, and
we'll settle a deal.

00:27:09.810 --> 00:27:13.060
Now I'm going to go to
the futures exchange.

00:27:13.060 --> 00:27:15.390
I've just bought a
quarter's worth of wheat

00:27:15.390 --> 00:27:16.484
from the wheat silo.

00:27:16.484 --> 00:27:18.150
I'm going to go to
the futures exchange,

00:27:18.150 --> 00:27:22.280
I'm going to sell a quarter's
worth of wheat forward.

00:27:22.280 --> 00:27:23.840
What have I done?

00:27:23.840 --> 00:27:26.550
Well, now I have no
price risk, right?

00:27:26.550 --> 00:27:28.560
Now if the price of
wheat goes up or down,

00:27:28.560 --> 00:27:30.461
I don't care, because
I bought we today,

00:27:30.461 --> 00:27:31.960
and I sold it three
months from now.

00:27:31.960 --> 00:27:34.672
I have borrowed wheat.

00:27:34.672 --> 00:27:35.880
Now, what could I do instead?

00:27:35.880 --> 00:27:36.760
I could borrow money.

00:27:36.760 --> 00:27:39.160
I could borrow money
and buy the wheat.

00:27:39.160 --> 00:27:41.050
But then I take
two price risks--

00:27:41.050 --> 00:27:43.559
I take the price risk of
the money, and remember,

00:27:43.559 --> 00:27:45.850
this is an area where there's
very little money around.

00:27:45.850 --> 00:27:47.070
These futures
exchanges were invented

00:27:47.070 --> 00:27:49.361
in a place where there was
very little gold and silver.

00:27:49.361 --> 00:27:51.570
There wasn't a good
banking system.

00:27:51.570 --> 00:27:53.830
Bank notes weren't
very trustworthy.

00:27:53.830 --> 00:27:56.570
So taking the risk of
money was a big risk.

00:27:56.570 --> 00:27:58.719
And also, price of
wheat going up and down.

00:27:58.719 --> 00:28:00.510
The simplest thing is
just to borrow wheat,

00:28:00.510 --> 00:28:02.490
which is what I want to do.

00:28:02.490 --> 00:28:06.140
And like any business loan,
I never intend to repay this.

00:28:06.140 --> 00:28:08.850
If I'm doing a business
loan, say to buy machinery,

00:28:08.850 --> 00:28:09.800
I make the loan.

00:28:09.800 --> 00:28:13.127
And when the loan comes
due, I borrow again

00:28:13.127 --> 00:28:13.960
to run the business.

00:28:13.960 --> 00:28:15.660
The only time I pay
back my business loans

00:28:15.660 --> 00:28:18.035
is when I shut down the business
and liquidate everything

00:28:18.035 --> 00:28:19.585
and pay off the creditors.

00:28:19.585 --> 00:28:20.460
Same thing with this.

00:28:20.460 --> 00:28:22.900
I'm going to roll these futures
contracts forward forever.

00:28:22.900 --> 00:28:25.100
I'm never going
to take delivery.

00:28:25.100 --> 00:28:27.930
But what I've done is I've
perpetually borrowed wheat.

00:28:27.930 --> 00:28:31.770
I've taken part of
my business input

00:28:31.770 --> 00:28:35.130
and I borrowed it
instead of buying it.

00:28:35.130 --> 00:28:38.160
So one thing is the
futures exchanges create

00:28:38.160 --> 00:28:40.454
a tremendous amount of credit.

00:28:40.454 --> 00:28:42.870
But they do something else too
that's kind of interesting.

00:28:42.870 --> 00:28:45.370
Anybody here know how to
take flour and turn it back

00:28:45.370 --> 00:28:45.885
into wheat?

00:28:49.600 --> 00:28:51.360
Anybody here know how
to take August wheat

00:28:51.360 --> 00:28:55.010
and move it back in time to May?

00:28:55.010 --> 00:28:58.000
All right, I have something
very surprising to tell you.

00:28:58.000 --> 00:29:01.570
For 175 years, the
Chicago Board of Trade

00:29:01.570 --> 00:29:05.030
here has been quoting prices
on both of those services.

00:29:05.030 --> 00:29:08.150
A futures exchange quotes
prices on services nobody's

00:29:08.150 --> 00:29:10.400
ever thought of.

00:29:10.400 --> 00:29:14.120
It opens tremendous
scope for innovation.

00:29:14.120 --> 00:29:15.834
Let's say I want
to build a bridge.

00:29:15.834 --> 00:29:17.250
And when I build
this bridge, it's

00:29:17.250 --> 00:29:19.839
going to divert wheat that
was going to Saint Louis.

00:29:19.839 --> 00:29:22.130
It's going to get diverted
to Chicago, because now it's

00:29:22.130 --> 00:29:24.600
going to be cheaper to
move it into Chicago.

00:29:24.600 --> 00:29:25.360
I can hedge that.

00:29:25.360 --> 00:29:29.120
I can sell those transportation
services on the futures market

00:29:29.120 --> 00:29:31.920
by buying Chicago wheat and
selling Saint Louis wheat.

00:29:34.920 --> 00:29:36.910
I can do calendar spreads.

00:29:36.910 --> 00:29:40.170
I can do grade spreads, cleaning
spreads, all of these things

00:29:40.170 --> 00:29:44.020
are a way of buying and selling
all the services involved

00:29:44.020 --> 00:29:50.370
in an agricultural
processing business.

00:29:50.370 --> 00:29:52.460
And this turns out to be
a far more efficient way

00:29:52.460 --> 00:29:53.300
to organize things.

00:29:53.300 --> 00:29:55.190
It's got its internally
generated credit.

00:29:55.190 --> 00:29:57.390
It's got far better
information flows.

00:29:57.390 --> 00:30:02.699
And this is what touches
off a tremendous explosion

00:30:02.699 --> 00:30:04.740
of business activity and
business innovation that

00:30:04.740 --> 00:30:07.470
goes throughout the world.

00:30:07.470 --> 00:30:10.210
Now, one of the things that's
kind of strange about futures

00:30:10.210 --> 00:30:12.817
markets is they were only used
for agricultural commodities.

00:30:12.817 --> 00:30:15.150
Now, granted, that was a much
bigger part of the economy

00:30:15.150 --> 00:30:17.560
than it is today, but
in the global economy,

00:30:17.560 --> 00:30:19.300
this was not a big deal.

00:30:19.300 --> 00:30:22.550
There were much, much more
valuable commodities that never

00:30:22.550 --> 00:30:24.250
went to futures exchanges.

00:30:24.250 --> 00:30:26.300
And there were things--
commodities weren't even

00:30:26.300 --> 00:30:29.640
the most valuable things.

00:30:29.640 --> 00:30:32.060
When things really took
off is in the 1970s

00:30:32.060 --> 00:30:36.970
when people took the same idea
and moved it to financial.

00:30:36.970 --> 00:30:43.394
But my story is about poker.

00:30:43.394 --> 00:30:44.810
One of the things
people sometimes

00:30:44.810 --> 00:30:48.410
say is that futures evolved
from to arrive contracts.

00:30:48.410 --> 00:30:51.110
Now, to arrive contracts
have been around longer

00:30:51.110 --> 00:30:52.750
than we have written records.

00:30:52.750 --> 00:30:54.970
In ancient Mesopotamia
in the early days,

00:30:54.970 --> 00:30:58.340
we see in the earliest writings
that we can still read today,

00:30:58.340 --> 00:31:02.140
we find that these to arrive
contracts were common.

00:31:02.140 --> 00:31:06.110
A to arrive contract
says, essentially,

00:31:06.110 --> 00:31:11.010
I will sell you 10,000 bushels
of wheat at $0.50 a bushel

00:31:11.010 --> 00:31:13.520
as soon as wheat
comes to the market,

00:31:13.520 --> 00:31:16.450
wheat come to the city market.

00:31:16.450 --> 00:31:17.660
OK, it's a price guarantee.

00:31:17.660 --> 00:31:18.910
It's not a delivery guarantee.

00:31:18.910 --> 00:31:20.610
I don't tell you when
you're going to get it.

00:31:20.610 --> 00:31:21.880
I don't even guarantee
you will get it.

00:31:21.880 --> 00:31:23.379
I'm just saying,
when it comes, this

00:31:23.379 --> 00:31:25.630
is what I will sell it you at.

00:31:25.630 --> 00:31:28.320
The largest to arrive
market in the United States

00:31:28.320 --> 00:31:30.980
was in Buffalo.

00:31:30.980 --> 00:31:35.140
OK, everybody remember all
those stories about the fortunes

00:31:35.140 --> 00:31:38.260
won and lost on the
Buffalo to arrive

00:31:38.260 --> 00:31:41.967
exchange, the
fistfights, the corners?

00:31:41.967 --> 00:31:44.050
We had people who made
their fortunes there, never

00:31:44.050 --> 00:31:45.424
went on do anything else?

00:31:45.424 --> 00:31:45.923
Exactly.

00:31:48.460 --> 00:31:53.040
To arrive contracts are run
by quiet commission clerks.

00:31:53.040 --> 00:31:57.530
Futures exchanges are populated
by tough, brawling innovators

00:31:57.530 --> 00:32:00.140
who often make fortunes
or lose fortunes and go on

00:32:00.140 --> 00:32:01.540
to do dramatic
business activity.

00:32:01.540 --> 00:32:04.530
There's no connection
between the two.

00:32:04.530 --> 00:32:08.642
Now, can anybody tell me which
ones of these are poker games?

00:32:08.642 --> 00:32:09.557
AUDIENCE: Omaha.

00:32:09.557 --> 00:32:10.265
PROFESSOR: Sorry?

00:32:10.265 --> 00:32:10.960
AUDIENCE: Omaha.

00:32:10.960 --> 00:32:11.910
PROFESSOR: Omaha, Texas.

00:32:11.910 --> 00:32:12.250
Yep.

00:32:12.250 --> 00:32:13.010
AUDIENCE: Chicago.

00:32:13.010 --> 00:32:14.567
PROFESSOR: Chicago, yes.

00:32:14.567 --> 00:32:16.650
This one you guys might
not have heard of so much,

00:32:16.650 --> 00:32:17.733
but there is a Cincinnati.

00:32:17.733 --> 00:32:20.670
It isn't played much anymore.

00:32:20.670 --> 00:32:23.130
There is no poker
game called Buffalo.

00:32:23.130 --> 00:32:27.760
There is no poker game named
after any place except places

00:32:27.760 --> 00:32:29.910
where, if you lose all
your money in the game,

00:32:29.910 --> 00:32:32.170
drown your servers by
jumping in a river,

00:32:32.170 --> 00:32:33.420
you float down to New Orleans.

00:32:37.390 --> 00:32:43.325
Even today, poker is very,
very strongly regionally-- it's

00:32:43.325 --> 00:32:44.820
a regional attitude.

00:32:44.820 --> 00:32:47.340
It's an extraordinarily
explosive innovative

00:32:47.340 --> 00:32:52.280
economic attitude, and it
has never really seeped out

00:32:52.280 --> 00:32:53.750
except the place it was born.

00:32:53.750 --> 00:32:57.600
Now, that may no longer be
true with internet poker.

00:32:57.600 --> 00:33:01.050
The question is, is the
soul of poker alive?

00:33:01.050 --> 00:33:05.070
Internet poker has this economic
innovation and freedom and self

00:33:05.070 --> 00:33:05.757
credit creation.

00:33:05.757 --> 00:33:08.340
Is this something's that's going
to spread to the whole world,

00:33:08.340 --> 00:33:10.350
or has somehow poker
been neutralized

00:33:10.350 --> 00:33:13.020
and, when it comes to a
computer and becomes virtual,

00:33:13.020 --> 00:33:14.515
it's no longer got that soul?

00:33:14.515 --> 00:33:18.540
It's something we're going to
find out in the next few years.

00:33:18.540 --> 00:33:21.130
Now we're going to
jump forward to me.

00:33:21.130 --> 00:33:23.810
I was born in the 1950s.

00:33:23.810 --> 00:33:27.111
I was raised in Seattle.

00:33:27.111 --> 00:33:28.610
And one thing you
have to understand

00:33:28.610 --> 00:33:32.150
is two people can be raised in
exactly the same time, exactly

00:33:32.150 --> 00:33:35.650
the same environment, and have
totally different ideas of what

00:33:35.650 --> 00:33:37.510
it was like.

00:33:37.510 --> 00:33:39.890
I think most people
would say, if a movie was

00:33:39.890 --> 00:33:41.640
made of my childhood,
they would say, hey,

00:33:41.640 --> 00:33:43.080
that was an idyllic childhood.

00:33:43.080 --> 00:33:44.467
Your dad was a professor.

00:33:44.467 --> 00:33:46.050
You didn't have so
much money that you

00:33:46.050 --> 00:33:49.675
had affluenza and were wrecking
cars or things like that.

00:33:49.675 --> 00:33:51.701
But you were never
embarrassed that you

00:33:51.701 --> 00:33:53.950
didn't have clothes for
school, you were never hungry,

00:33:53.950 --> 00:33:55.430
anything like that.

00:33:55.430 --> 00:33:56.350
You were treated well.

00:33:56.350 --> 00:33:57.630
It was a suburban neighborhood.

00:33:57.630 --> 00:33:58.546
It was a pretty place.

00:33:58.546 --> 00:34:00.690
You had lots of stimulation,
all of that stuff.

00:34:00.690 --> 00:34:03.780
But I hated it.

00:34:03.780 --> 00:34:07.020
I was oppressed
by lots of things.

00:34:07.020 --> 00:34:08.895
I believed, I
sincerely believed,

00:34:08.895 --> 00:34:10.880
that the world was going
to end in nuclear war

00:34:10.880 --> 00:34:12.480
before I was in college.

00:34:12.480 --> 00:34:15.428
It just seemed like it
clearly was likely to happen.

00:34:15.428 --> 00:34:16.969
I was interested in
math and science,

00:34:16.969 --> 00:34:20.050
but all the math and
science was defense related.

00:34:20.050 --> 00:34:22.150
Only big government
projects to kill

00:34:22.150 --> 00:34:26.860
people were the only way you
could get funding for things.

00:34:26.860 --> 00:34:32.070
More than half the world was in
the grip of brutal totalitarian

00:34:32.070 --> 00:34:36.370
dictatorships, and no country
had ever emerged from communism

00:34:36.370 --> 00:34:38.618
to freedom and prosperity.

00:34:38.618 --> 00:34:42.590
It seemed like the entire,
world even the free world, even

00:34:42.590 --> 00:34:45.460
the relative democracies,
were run by paranoids

00:34:45.460 --> 00:34:47.760
and total incompetents.

00:34:47.760 --> 00:34:49.170
The economy was terrible.

00:34:49.170 --> 00:34:51.659
Seattle was a few years ahead
of the rest of the country

00:34:51.659 --> 00:34:55.090
and we had sort of slipped
into that '70s malaise

00:34:55.090 --> 00:34:56.889
back in the '60s.

