A friend of the family who
was an aerospace engineer who

00:34:59.420 --> 00:35:02.190
was the world expert--
in fact, he went to MIT.

00:35:02.190 --> 00:35:05.460
He was the world expert in
materials for supersonic wing

00:35:05.460 --> 00:35:06.630
design.

00:35:06.630 --> 00:35:08.310
He was fired because
nobody wanted

00:35:08.310 --> 00:35:10.890
to build supersonic planes,
and he was driving a cab.

00:35:10.890 --> 00:35:13.327
Another thing about this
is this is, again, Seattle

00:35:13.327 --> 00:35:15.410
was kind of forward looking
in terms of economics.

00:35:15.410 --> 00:35:18.167
We were getting economic malaise
before the rest of the country.

00:35:18.167 --> 00:35:20.000
In another way, we were
kind of a throwback.

00:35:20.000 --> 00:35:24.230
It was more like the '50s than
other parts of the country.

00:35:24.230 --> 00:35:27.809
And it was this really
weird social dynamic.

00:35:27.809 --> 00:35:30.100
OK, I don't want to tell you
the neighborhood I grew up

00:35:30.100 --> 00:35:33.380
in was any worse or weirder
than any other neighborhood.

00:35:33.380 --> 00:35:36.020
But there was a certain
percentage of alcoholics,

00:35:36.020 --> 00:35:39.476
or child molesters,
of wife beaters,

00:35:39.476 --> 00:35:42.030
of drug addicts, all the stuff.

00:35:42.030 --> 00:35:47.004
And in the '50s and in Seattle
by the time I was growing up,

00:35:47.004 --> 00:35:47.920
nobody cared about it.

00:35:47.920 --> 00:35:50.210
Nobody would ever talk
about any of that stuff.

00:35:50.210 --> 00:35:54.540
If a man cut his grass and
brought home a paycheck,

00:35:54.540 --> 00:35:55.460
he was a good guy.

00:35:55.460 --> 00:35:59.280
He could do anything else and
nobody would talk about it.

00:35:59.280 --> 00:36:01.414
But if you didn't--
and we would have this.

00:36:01.414 --> 00:36:02.080
It would happen.

00:36:02.080 --> 00:36:04.926
Like a neighbor, the
guy would lose this job.

00:36:04.926 --> 00:36:07.050
They would quietly move
away, and nobody would ever

00:36:07.050 --> 00:36:08.860
talk about them.

00:36:08.860 --> 00:36:10.420
It was just weird.

00:36:10.420 --> 00:36:14.450
And you got the message, OK,
the economy was very insecure.

00:36:14.450 --> 00:36:16.616
If you could earn money,
everything was fine.

00:36:16.616 --> 00:36:18.490
You didn't have to worry
about anything else.

00:36:18.490 --> 00:36:23.020
But if you couldn't earn
money, it was unspeakably bad.

00:36:23.020 --> 00:36:24.340
Well, I was a shy kid.

00:36:24.340 --> 00:36:27.750
I was introverted, awkward.

00:36:27.750 --> 00:36:31.509
But I liked looking in the back
of a newspaper at the numbers.

00:36:31.509 --> 00:36:33.550
The patterns in the numbers
really fascinated me.

00:36:33.550 --> 00:36:37.285
And I worked out ways, and
I would bet money on horses,

00:36:37.285 --> 00:36:39.435
I would bet money
on other sports.

00:36:39.435 --> 00:36:42.051
And I found out I
could win doing this.

00:36:42.051 --> 00:36:44.550
I also found out-- and this was
true throughout the American

00:36:44.550 --> 00:36:45.600
West at the time.

00:36:45.600 --> 00:36:47.590
I couldn't really find
a good picture of this.

00:36:47.590 --> 00:36:49.798
This is just something I
found on the internet that's

00:36:49.798 --> 00:36:51.420
roughly equivalent.

00:36:51.420 --> 00:36:53.150
Taverns, in the back
room of the taverns

00:36:53.150 --> 00:36:56.400
or the basement of the taverns,
there were these poker games.

00:36:56.400 --> 00:37:01.360
And I'd go in and I'd
play, and I'd win.

00:37:01.360 --> 00:37:06.510
And more important than that
I would win, I could walk in.

00:37:06.510 --> 00:37:07.980
I could collect the money.

00:37:07.980 --> 00:37:14.000
I could walk out, and this was
enormously liberating to me.

00:37:14.000 --> 00:37:15.180
It said to me, OK.

00:37:15.180 --> 00:37:16.420
You don't have to get a job.

00:37:16.420 --> 00:37:18.540
You don't have to go to college.

00:37:18.540 --> 00:37:21.090
Anywhere you go in the world,
you can find a poker game.

00:37:21.090 --> 00:37:22.690
You can win money.

00:37:22.690 --> 00:37:25.204
And when you're a good
player and people know it,

00:37:25.204 --> 00:37:27.370
even if you run out of
money, people lend you money.

00:37:27.370 --> 00:37:29.882
People stake you.

00:37:29.882 --> 00:37:32.329
You also start getting
into this network.

00:37:32.329 --> 00:37:34.370
And this was something I
had not expected at all.

00:37:34.370 --> 00:37:35.390
I had gone there, I thought, OK.

00:37:35.390 --> 00:37:36.889
I'm going to win
some money, and I'm

00:37:36.889 --> 00:37:39.790
going to prove that I can
get this monkey off my back

00:37:39.790 --> 00:37:42.400
and I don't have to
worry about this anymore.

00:37:42.400 --> 00:37:44.240
These people-- the
people I was playing with

00:37:44.240 --> 00:37:44.760
didn't look like this.

00:37:44.760 --> 00:37:46.770
One or two of them might
have looked like this.

00:37:46.770 --> 00:37:48.770
But there were policemen,
there were sailors,

00:37:48.770 --> 00:37:49.580
there were clerks.

00:37:49.580 --> 00:37:50.760
You know, people.

00:37:50.760 --> 00:37:52.861
And they end up owing you money.

00:37:52.861 --> 00:37:54.610
Right, if you're good
player, these people

00:37:54.610 --> 00:37:56.580
end up owing you money.

00:37:56.580 --> 00:37:58.190
And I later kind of
figured, I sort of

00:37:58.190 --> 00:38:00.150
had a half idea of what
was going on at the time.

00:38:00.150 --> 00:38:02.066
But I've later figured
it out a little better,

00:38:02.066 --> 00:38:04.730
and later in life as
I've played more places,

00:38:04.730 --> 00:38:09.050
I've figured out the
system a little better.

00:38:09.050 --> 00:38:11.340
I had a purpose
for these people.

00:38:11.340 --> 00:38:13.660
I had two purposes.

00:38:13.660 --> 00:38:17.997
One is because I was a good
player I protected their game.

00:38:17.997 --> 00:38:20.080
Let's say somebody showed
up, a really good player

00:38:20.080 --> 00:38:21.480
wanted to take all
their money, show up

00:38:21.480 --> 00:38:23.300
and-- well, they had
somebody there who was good.

00:38:23.300 --> 00:38:25.591
And by the way, being a good
poker player in those days

00:38:25.591 --> 00:38:27.890
didn't just mean good card play.

00:38:27.890 --> 00:38:32.840
In fact, it would be trivially--
and I'm sure anybody here

00:38:32.840 --> 00:38:36.020
what have no trouble cleaning
up in terms of pure card play

00:38:36.020 --> 00:38:37.580
in this game.

00:38:37.580 --> 00:38:39.570
But you had to be
able to spot cheating.

00:38:39.570 --> 00:38:43.197
You had to be able to figure
out who might risk of arrest.

00:38:43.197 --> 00:38:45.030
You had to figure out
who might get violent.

00:38:45.030 --> 00:38:48.120
I mean, there's a lot of
social skills involved in this.

00:38:48.120 --> 00:38:51.670
So by being a good player,
you protected the game,

00:38:51.670 --> 00:38:55.340
but you also connected
them with a bigger network.

00:38:55.340 --> 00:38:57.675
So remember, a lot of this
is about credit equation.

00:38:57.675 --> 00:39:00.700
A tremendous amount of
economic activity goes on here.

00:39:03.660 --> 00:39:07.560
There's doctors, lawyers,
police, mechanics,

00:39:07.560 --> 00:39:12.660
whatever-- people exchanging
services, underground economy,

00:39:12.660 --> 00:39:15.380
people who couldn't make
it in the normal economy.

00:39:15.380 --> 00:39:18.920
Like let's say you're a lawyer,
and you're a really bad lawyer.

00:39:18.920 --> 00:39:20.300
And you can't get any business.

00:39:20.300 --> 00:39:21.630
You hang [? out a shingle, ?]
nobody's going to hire you.

00:39:21.630 --> 00:39:22.796
Your resume isn't very good.

00:39:22.796 --> 00:39:24.290
There's too many lawyers around.

00:39:24.290 --> 00:39:27.956
But you know, you owe
somebody money at a poker game

00:39:27.956 --> 00:39:30.330
and they want you to write a
letter and do some for them,

00:39:30.330 --> 00:39:33.840
whenever, you can do a little
legal business on this stuff.

00:39:33.840 --> 00:39:38.180
And by connecting into the
broader network in the city,

00:39:38.180 --> 00:39:40.150
you connect these people in.

00:39:40.150 --> 00:39:43.260
Some of these people had really
dropped out of normal life,

00:39:43.260 --> 00:39:45.686
or they weren't
getting paychecks.

00:39:45.686 --> 00:39:48.060
They were subsisting entirely
on the underground economy.

00:39:48.060 --> 00:39:50.143
And this was a very important
organizational tool.

00:39:50.143 --> 00:39:51.620
Other people like
to keep one foot

00:39:51.620 --> 00:39:54.630
in that world-- maybe a
little side income, maybe

00:39:54.630 --> 00:39:55.380
a little fallback.

00:39:58.060 --> 00:40:00.170
We weren't doing like
big organized crime,

00:40:00.170 --> 00:40:01.980
but there'd be a
sailor in the game who

00:40:01.980 --> 00:40:03.884
could bring in Cuban cigars.

00:40:03.884 --> 00:40:05.550
There was a guy who
was maybe a bathroom

00:40:05.550 --> 00:40:07.990
attendant at a fancy
restaurant who could sell them,

00:40:07.990 --> 00:40:12.570
and this kind of stuff could get
organized in a game like this.

00:40:12.570 --> 00:40:15.970
The poker was very important
because you actually

00:40:15.970 --> 00:40:17.910
spend a lot of time
with these people.

00:40:17.910 --> 00:40:19.540
You learned a lot about them.

00:40:19.540 --> 00:40:21.880
You couldn't fake it in a way.

00:40:21.880 --> 00:40:24.807
An undercover cop could
show up for two days

00:40:24.807 --> 00:40:26.390
or act something
this, but they aren't

00:40:26.390 --> 00:40:30.130
going to be playing poker
every day for years.

00:40:30.130 --> 00:40:35.900
So I'm kind of moving up in
the Seattle poker network,

00:40:35.900 --> 00:40:37.070
and I come to Boston.

00:40:37.070 --> 00:40:39.330
I went to Harvard.

00:40:39.330 --> 00:40:41.700
And again, remember, I'm shy.

00:40:41.700 --> 00:40:42.520
I'm awkward.

00:40:42.520 --> 00:40:48.460
I'm from the west, a little
overwhelmed by all this stuff.

00:40:48.460 --> 00:40:50.580
But I walked in with a network.

00:40:50.580 --> 00:40:53.170
It shocked me when I got
here that this network was

00:40:53.170 --> 00:40:59.210
seamlessly translated across
the country, that I knew police,

00:40:59.210 --> 00:41:05.410
I knew poker people of all
different ranks and stations

00:41:05.410 --> 00:41:07.390
of life.

00:41:07.390 --> 00:41:10.750
I got into poker games
at Harvard itself.

00:41:10.750 --> 00:41:13.495
People talk about going to
college to get contacts.

00:41:13.495 --> 00:41:14.620
Let me tell you about that.

00:41:14.620 --> 00:41:15.600
I had three roommates.

00:41:15.600 --> 00:41:16.220
I love my roommates.

00:41:16.220 --> 00:41:17.010
These are great guys.

00:41:17.010 --> 00:41:18.680
I'm not saying anything
bad about them.

00:41:18.680 --> 00:41:23.170
But in terms of like useful
contacts for me in life,

00:41:23.170 --> 00:41:25.420
well, one of them's a
corporate lawyer, one of them's

00:41:25.420 --> 00:41:27.620
a TV producer, one of
them's a law professor--

00:41:27.620 --> 00:41:29.060
all great things, that's nice.

00:41:29.060 --> 00:41:31.000
Never really a lot
of use to me in terms

00:41:31.000 --> 00:41:34.580
of advancing my business
interests or whatever,

00:41:34.580 --> 00:41:37.611
and not exactly hard things
to break into, right?

00:41:37.611 --> 00:41:39.110
You want to know a
corporate lawyer?

00:41:39.110 --> 00:41:42.970
Well, it's pretty easy to
know a corporate lawyer.

00:41:42.970 --> 00:41:46.344
Poker games at Harvard, I
played with George W. Bush,

00:41:46.344 --> 00:41:47.510
who went on to be president.

00:41:47.510 --> 00:41:51.710
I played with Bill Gates,
Steve Ballmer, Scott Turow,

00:41:51.710 --> 00:41:55.987
people who are celebrities,
politicians, rich people.

00:41:55.987 --> 00:41:57.320
Those are the poker connections.

00:41:57.320 --> 00:41:59.550
And a poker connection
is very different.

00:41:59.550 --> 00:42:01.660
You're not playing
poker with your friends.

00:42:01.660 --> 00:42:03.640
A poker connection is,
there is a business

00:42:03.640 --> 00:42:06.484
relationship in there that
can be extremely useful.

00:42:06.484 --> 00:42:08.150
My whole life, my
whole career, has been

00:42:08.150 --> 00:42:12.460
informed by poker networks.

00:42:12.460 --> 00:42:16.450
Now I'm going to zip
through a few things.

00:42:16.450 --> 00:42:19.250
I'm playing in Boston,
a guy shows up.

00:42:19.250 --> 00:42:22.220
He actually managed a card
room near Stanford University.

00:42:22.220 --> 00:42:25.040
He was, again, it's
this network thing.

00:42:25.040 --> 00:42:27.720
So I'm playing now in a
pretty senior game in Boston,

00:42:27.720 --> 00:42:29.220
some the best card
players in Boston

00:42:29.220 --> 00:42:32.640
are here, pretty high stakes.

00:42:32.640 --> 00:42:36.350
And they invite visiting pros
from other parts of the country

00:42:36.350 --> 00:42:40.800
to keep the network connected
throughout the country.

00:42:40.800 --> 00:42:45.310
And this guy said to me,
he said, well, I was good.

00:42:45.310 --> 00:42:46.770
I played well that night.

00:42:46.770 --> 00:42:47.790
But it wasn't just that.

00:42:47.790 --> 00:42:50.320
He said, you know, you're
a kind of strange guy.

00:42:50.320 --> 00:42:52.890
You've got this sort of
mathematical poker sense.

00:42:52.890 --> 00:42:55.460
You think about it in
theoretical terms, whatever.

00:42:55.460 --> 00:42:58.130
There are a lot of guys like
you out in Gardena, California.

00:42:58.130 --> 00:43:02.040
So that's where the best poker
in the world is being played.

00:43:02.040 --> 00:43:03.610
He said, I'm a good player.

00:43:03.610 --> 00:43:05.320
I'm a national pro.

00:43:05.320 --> 00:43:07.580
I go around from city to
city sitting in end games

00:43:07.580 --> 00:43:08.996
with the best
players in the city.

00:43:08.996 --> 00:43:12.890
And I win in those games, but I
can't turn a profit in Gardena.

00:43:12.890 --> 00:43:15.720
You should go the Gardena and
see if you can match yourself

00:43:15.720 --> 00:43:18.480
up with the best.

00:43:18.480 --> 00:43:19.730
So I go there.

00:43:19.730 --> 00:43:22.520
How many people have heard
of Gardena, California?

00:43:22.520 --> 00:43:23.400
Yeah.

00:43:23.400 --> 00:43:26.290
If you're interested, there's
a movie called California Split

00:43:26.290 --> 00:43:27.560
that's got some good scenes.

00:43:27.560 --> 00:43:29.510
It's stupid poker movie
for the most part,

00:43:29.510 --> 00:43:33.380
but it has some actual scenes
shot in Gardena at that time.

00:43:33.380 --> 00:43:35.910
That was the best
poker in the world.

00:43:35.910 --> 00:43:41.090
And it was the network theory
I was talking about on steroids

00:43:41.090 --> 00:43:42.570
because of a few things.

00:43:42.570 --> 00:43:44.969
First of all, this
is in the late '70s.

00:43:44.969 --> 00:43:46.760
Marginal tax rates have
gotten really high,

00:43:46.760 --> 00:43:48.820
regulation has gotten
crazy, the tax code

00:43:48.820 --> 00:43:51.320
is incredibly
complicated and corrupt.

00:43:51.320 --> 00:43:53.840
Community property, big
thing-- a lot of these guys

00:43:53.840 --> 00:43:55.007
were wiped out in a divorce.

00:43:55.007 --> 00:43:56.506
I mean, that was
something that just

00:43:56.506 --> 00:43:58.220
didn't happen 10 years earlier.

00:43:58.220 --> 00:43:59.792
A lot of them had tax liens.

00:43:59.792 --> 00:44:02.250
So you have this whole group
of people, they tend be-- they

00:44:02.250 --> 00:44:04.860
were much better
educated than the guys

00:44:04.860 --> 00:44:09.210
I was playing with in Seattle or
even really the guys in Boston.

00:44:09.210 --> 00:44:10.570
They were smart.

00:44:10.570 --> 00:44:13.594
Not only were they broke,
they were financially toxic.

00:44:13.594 --> 00:44:15.260
Any money they put
in a bank was getting

00:44:15.260 --> 00:44:16.800
whisked away by somebody.

00:44:16.800 --> 00:44:19.500
If they were walking down the
street with $1 in their pocket,

00:44:19.500 --> 00:44:21.170
somebody could grab it.

00:44:21.170 --> 00:44:24.060
Poker chip, not so much, right?

00:44:24.060 --> 00:44:27.540
Poker debt, they lent some money
to somebody in the poker room,

00:44:27.540 --> 00:44:29.530
nobody could collect that.

00:44:29.530 --> 00:44:34.400
Tremendous about of very active
underground economy going on.

00:44:34.400 --> 00:44:36.850
I go there, and first day I'm
there, guy comes up to me.

00:44:36.850 --> 00:44:38.310
He manages a motel.

00:44:38.310 --> 00:44:40.907
He used to own
it, went bankrupt.

00:44:40.907 --> 00:44:42.365
Now the bank pays
him to manage it.

00:44:45.890 --> 00:44:48.744
If you're a poker player, he'll
give you a room to stay in.

00:44:48.744 --> 00:44:49.410
You have to pay.

00:44:49.410 --> 00:44:50.990
You slip him a
little bit of money,

00:44:50.990 --> 00:44:52.792
much less than
the rent would be.

00:44:52.792 --> 00:44:55.250
It's kind of furnished with
broken down stuff other tenants

00:44:55.250 --> 00:44:55.780
have left.

00:44:55.780 --> 00:44:57.160
But poker players
don't care, right?

00:44:57.160 --> 00:44:58.260
Poker players are
there, they go,

00:44:58.260 --> 00:45:00.620
they sleep on the broken
couch, and then they leave.

00:45:00.620 --> 00:45:04.180
Maybe take a shower if
it's the first of the month

00:45:04.180 --> 00:45:06.920
or something.

00:45:06.920 --> 00:45:08.860
And you'd stay there for
three or four months,

00:45:08.860 --> 00:45:11.820
and eventually the owners
would kick you out.

00:45:11.820 --> 00:45:14.540
And he'd just say, oh, well,
the guy never paid any rent,

00:45:14.540 --> 00:45:16.559
and he would cover all
this for you and do it.

00:45:16.559 --> 00:45:18.850
And then you just move to
the next motel down the line,

00:45:18.850 --> 00:45:20.505
and he moves somebody else in.

00:45:20.505 --> 00:45:21.880
You wanted to get
your car fixed,

00:45:21.880 --> 00:45:24.250
you wanted to get
a lawsuit filed,

00:45:24.250 --> 00:45:28.260
you wanted to get
your operation done,

00:45:28.260 --> 00:45:30.820
whatever, there were people
in the room to do it,

00:45:30.820 --> 00:45:34.070
all for under the table,
you could borrow the money.

00:45:34.070 --> 00:45:37.560
And all of the people who can
invented the modern poker,

00:45:37.560 --> 00:45:40.210
if you talk about the David
Sklansky's, Mason Malmuth, Mike

00:45:40.210 --> 00:45:40.710
Harrow.

00:45:40.710 --> 00:45:42.600
I don't know if these
names mean anything to you,

00:45:42.600 --> 00:45:44.900
but these were the first people
who actually sat down and wrote

00:45:44.900 --> 00:45:45.795
poker theory books.

00:45:45.795 --> 00:45:47.940
This was the only place
where people were really

00:45:47.940 --> 00:45:48.970
thinking about it.

00:45:48.970 --> 00:45:51.100
Las Vegas, they hated poker.

00:45:51.100 --> 00:45:52.930
Casinos hate poker.

00:45:52.930 --> 00:45:55.490
The reason casinos hated poker
is somebody in the building

00:45:55.490 --> 00:45:58.724
was losing money and the
Casino wasn't getting it.

00:45:58.724 --> 00:46:01.140
And they would stick it-- they
either wouldn't have poker,

00:46:01.140 --> 00:46:03.080
or they'd stick it next to
the layout of slot machines

00:46:03.080 --> 00:46:03.970
under the stairs.

00:46:03.970 --> 00:46:06.140
They'd open and close the
room at random intervals.

00:46:06.140 --> 00:46:08.348
The one thing they did was
the World Series of Poker.

00:46:08.348 --> 00:46:09.950
It was a pure Casino
publicity stunt.

