00:48:34.742 --> 00:48:37.415
Now, all of us had read Ed
Thorpe's Beat the Dealer.

00:48:37.415 --> 00:48:39.876
Do people here know Ed Thorpe?

00:48:39.876 --> 00:48:40.500
OK, you should.

00:48:40.500 --> 00:48:41.877
You should read his books.

00:48:41.877 --> 00:48:42.710
You should meet him.

00:48:42.710 --> 00:48:44.700
He's still alive.

00:48:44.700 --> 00:48:47.280
He was a mathematics professor.

00:48:47.280 --> 00:48:48.870
He invented blackjack
card counting.

00:48:48.870 --> 00:48:52.350
He managed to beat virtually
every other Casino game.

00:48:52.350 --> 00:48:56.972
And he's also either invented
or perfected almost all

00:48:56.972 --> 00:48:58.680
of the quantitative
hedge fund strategies

00:48:58.680 --> 00:48:59.690
that people use today.

00:48:59.690 --> 00:49:02.910
He was one of the most
successful hedge fund managers

00:49:02.910 --> 00:49:05.110
for many years.

00:49:05.110 --> 00:49:09.279
So one thing we did is we wanted
to go and beat casino games.

00:49:09.279 --> 00:49:10.820
And then what I'd
like to talk about,

00:49:10.820 --> 00:49:12.653
I'm just going to mention
this very briefly.

00:49:12.653 --> 00:49:15.874
But roulette, to
me, was the one that

00:49:15.874 --> 00:49:18.040
really changed the way I
think about a lot of stuff.

00:49:18.040 --> 00:49:19.600
It's a very, very
important lesson

00:49:19.600 --> 00:49:23.360
for people who have academic
statistics backgrounds.

00:49:23.360 --> 00:49:25.140
How do you beat roulette?

00:49:25.140 --> 00:49:27.550
OK, well this Ed Thorpe's.

00:49:27.550 --> 00:49:29.510
Ed Thorpe was
thinking about this.

00:49:29.510 --> 00:49:32.950
And he was hearing this
debate, and some people said,

00:49:32.950 --> 00:49:34.640
you should [INAUDIBLE]
You should just

00:49:34.640 --> 00:49:36.140
record the patterns
of the wheels

00:49:36.140 --> 00:49:37.830
and see if you can notice
patterns, like the wheel's

00:49:37.830 --> 00:49:39.480
a little weighted,
what number comes up

00:49:39.480 --> 00:49:40.890
a little more than the others.

00:49:40.890 --> 00:49:43.500
But other people said
no, that's impossible.

00:49:43.500 --> 00:49:45.340
The wheels are too good.

00:49:45.340 --> 00:49:48.060
And Ed had a really remarkable
insight that not enough people

00:49:48.060 --> 00:49:48.700
know about.

00:49:48.700 --> 00:49:51.980
He said, you can win
money either way.

00:49:51.980 --> 00:49:55.500
If the wheel's broken and
13 comes up a little more

00:49:55.500 --> 00:49:57.280
than it should,
you can bet on 13.

00:49:57.280 --> 00:49:58.890
That's easy.

00:49:58.890 --> 00:50:02.130
But if the wheel is so perfect
that every number comes

00:50:02.130 --> 00:50:04.764
up equally often, it must
be machined to perfection,

00:50:04.764 --> 00:50:06.180
then you can use
a little physics.

00:50:06.180 --> 00:50:09.610
We had some mechanics up on
the board when I came here.

00:50:09.610 --> 00:50:13.230
Use Newtonian physics, and
you can figure out where

00:50:13.230 --> 00:50:15.920
the ball is going to end up.

00:50:15.920 --> 00:50:17.130
So it's a lot of work.

00:50:17.130 --> 00:50:18.390
He did it with Claude Shannon.

00:50:18.390 --> 00:50:22.315
Again, we're back to
MIT, one of the fathers

00:50:22.315 --> 00:50:23.900
of information theory.

00:50:23.900 --> 00:50:26.540
And they sat down, and
they worked on roulette.

00:50:26.540 --> 00:50:28.510
And if you study this
problem for a bit,

00:50:28.510 --> 00:50:33.020
you pretty quickly find
out, here's how things work.

00:50:33.020 --> 00:50:35.570
The way roulette works, they
spin a wheel in one direction,

00:50:35.570 --> 00:50:37.290
and they spin a ball
around the outside

00:50:37.290 --> 00:50:39.420
of a bowl the other way.

00:50:39.420 --> 00:50:45.440
OK, everything is very Newtonian
until the ball goes away

00:50:45.440 --> 00:50:46.610
from the edge.

00:50:46.610 --> 00:50:49.557
It is very easy with a little
bit of electronic aids--

00:50:49.557 --> 00:50:51.640
which at the time were
legal, and are now illegal.

00:50:51.640 --> 00:50:55.130
But with electronic
aids, it's very easy

00:50:55.130 --> 00:50:58.350
to tell what number
will be under the ball

00:50:58.350 --> 00:51:01.040
when the ball leaves the edge.

00:51:01.040 --> 00:51:03.220
Now, there's a lot of
bouncing and banging

00:51:03.220 --> 00:51:06.610
around between that and
when the ball comes to rest.

00:51:06.610 --> 00:51:08.480
And that's pretty
chaotic, essentially

00:51:08.480 --> 00:51:10.700
impossible to predict.

00:51:10.700 --> 00:51:13.550
So you have this perfectly
predictable section,

00:51:13.550 --> 00:51:15.940
and then you have
this chaotic section.

00:51:15.940 --> 00:51:18.740
But here's the insight.

00:51:18.740 --> 00:51:21.050
The predictable section,
you can calculate.

00:51:21.050 --> 00:51:21.800
You can know, OK.

00:51:21.800 --> 00:51:23.591
You say, when the ball
goes under the edge,

00:51:23.591 --> 00:51:26.340
number 17 will be
directly underneath it.

00:51:26.340 --> 00:51:30.224
The chaotic part cannot
be uniform on the wheel.

00:51:30.224 --> 00:51:33.560
You can say, if 17 is under
it when the ball comes down,

00:51:33.560 --> 00:51:35.132
here is the
distribution of places

00:51:35.132 --> 00:51:36.840
the ball is going to
end up on the wheel,

00:51:36.840 --> 00:51:40.250
and it's nowhere near
random, nowhere near uniform.

00:51:40.250 --> 00:51:42.290
So you can make good bets.

00:51:42.290 --> 00:51:44.279
Now if you actually
want to do this,

00:51:44.279 --> 00:51:45.570
you have to get several layers.

00:51:45.570 --> 00:51:49.400
You have to keep
refining this notion.

00:51:49.400 --> 00:51:53.190
But I just want to focus
on the big picture.

00:51:53.190 --> 00:51:55.820
A lot of statistical theory,
the basic theory of statistics,

00:51:55.820 --> 00:51:57.130
was based on dice.

00:51:57.130 --> 00:52:00.620
That's what Nassim Taleb calls
the ludic fallacy-- people

00:52:00.620 --> 00:52:03.160
trying to create randomness.

00:52:03.160 --> 00:52:07.020
The real world is
nowhere near so random.

00:52:07.020 --> 00:52:10.860
Even when people try to create
randomness, even in a Casino,

00:52:10.860 --> 00:52:12.930
they can't do it.

00:52:12.930 --> 00:52:16.620
And the reason they can't do it
is if you build things really,

00:52:16.620 --> 00:52:19.600
really precisely,
they're predictable.

00:52:19.600 --> 00:52:22.470
If you build things kind
of loose and sloppy,

00:52:22.470 --> 00:52:25.690
they have non-uniform patterns.

00:52:25.690 --> 00:52:28.960
What you can't do is build
a device that's both.

00:52:28.960 --> 00:52:31.680
It exceeds human capabilities.

00:52:31.680 --> 00:52:34.480
And when we're talking about
the practical randomness

00:52:34.480 --> 00:52:39.720
you see in the world-- in the
stock market, in politics,

00:52:39.720 --> 00:52:42.840
and in war, anything you
want to talk about-- people

00:52:42.840 --> 00:52:46.070
are way too sloppy in
modeling things as random.

00:52:46.070 --> 00:52:48.800
Whenever somebody says
this thing is random,

00:52:48.800 --> 00:52:50.950
you say, I'm going
to take a hard block.

00:52:50.950 --> 00:52:53.420
And I'm going to find little
pockets of predictability

00:52:53.420 --> 00:52:55.270
that I can calculate.

00:52:55.270 --> 00:52:57.370
And in between those
pockets of predictability,

00:52:57.370 --> 00:53:01.101
I'm going to find patterns
that are non-uniform.

00:53:01.101 --> 00:53:02.600
And what I'm going
to end up with is

00:53:02.600 --> 00:53:05.016
I'm going to end up with a
system where people are saying,

00:53:05.016 --> 00:53:08.224
you know, you're obsessing
about data and data quality

00:53:08.224 --> 00:53:10.140
for things that don't
really matter very much.

00:53:10.140 --> 00:53:12.223
Nobody else thinks these
statistics are important.

00:53:12.223 --> 00:53:14.220
Why are you spending
all your time

00:53:14.220 --> 00:53:15.650
cleaning data for
something that's

00:53:15.650 --> 00:53:19.440
far removed from the essential
economics of this problem?

00:53:19.440 --> 00:53:21.260
And they're also going
to say, and here are

00:53:21.260 --> 00:53:22.990
the really important things.

00:53:22.990 --> 00:53:24.670
And you're just
waving your hands.

00:53:24.670 --> 00:53:25.836
You're not paying attention.

00:53:25.836 --> 00:53:28.610
You're making criminally
reckless or crude assumptions

00:53:28.610 --> 00:53:30.196
about those things.

00:53:30.196 --> 00:53:31.570
But what they
don't understand is

00:53:31.570 --> 00:53:34.180
that's exactly how you beat it.

00:53:34.180 --> 00:53:35.470
That is what you do.

00:53:35.470 --> 00:53:37.720
When you figure this stuff
out, you really come up

00:53:37.720 --> 00:53:42.390
with this thing that will
understand and make a profit,

00:53:42.390 --> 00:53:44.340
it will look like
that to outsiders,

00:53:44.340 --> 00:53:46.340
that you're focused on
stuff that doesn't matter

00:53:46.340 --> 00:53:48.510
and you're ignoring the
stuff that does matter.

00:53:48.510 --> 00:53:50.310
Put another way,
the stuff you think

00:53:50.310 --> 00:53:52.710
that matters doesn't,
and the stuff you

00:53:52.710 --> 00:53:54.160
don't think that matters does.

00:53:54.160 --> 00:53:56.243
And when you do enough
work on this kind of stuff,

00:53:56.243 --> 00:53:58.550
that's how you win.

00:53:58.550 --> 00:54:00.520
Now, the thing
about the people who

00:54:00.520 --> 00:54:04.320
did blackjack card counting and
roulette and baccarat and craps

00:54:04.320 --> 00:54:07.600
worked on all those
other games, what

00:54:07.600 --> 00:54:13.200
happens when people find out
that's what they're doing?

00:54:13.200 --> 00:54:14.480
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

