But you do got to be
able to look around

00:57:27.590 --> 00:57:29.859
the people at the table
and figure some stuff out.

00:57:29.859 --> 00:57:31.775
You've got to be able
to get invited to games.

00:57:31.775 --> 00:57:33.649
You've got to be able
to collect from losers.

00:57:33.649 --> 00:57:37.240
You've got to be able to avoid
arrest or getting cheated

00:57:37.240 --> 00:57:39.540
or beaten up and
stuff like that.

00:57:39.540 --> 00:57:42.840
So we were kind of in between.

00:57:42.840 --> 00:57:45.420
So a lot of people I know
from those days-- this

00:57:45.420 --> 00:57:49.710
was the '70s, '80s, early '80s--
a lot of people stayed at it.

00:57:49.710 --> 00:57:52.110
But a lot of us, having
honed our skills and figured,

00:57:52.110 --> 00:57:56.050
OK, now we think
we know something.

00:57:56.050 --> 00:57:58.110
I've been playing
poker since I'm 14.

00:57:58.110 --> 00:58:02.971
I've had moderate success in
beating casino games and sports

00:58:02.971 --> 00:58:03.470
betting.

00:58:03.470 --> 00:58:06.070
I've had some really
strong success at poker.

00:58:06.070 --> 00:58:07.380
I have some confidence, right?

00:58:07.380 --> 00:58:09.130
I don't just think
I know something.

00:58:09.130 --> 00:58:09.860
I know something.

00:58:09.860 --> 00:58:13.230
And the reason I believe it
is I've went to the places

00:58:13.230 --> 00:58:15.307
where you test that
stuff and walked away

00:58:15.307 --> 00:58:16.140
with people's money.

00:58:18.670 --> 00:58:21.280
So a lot of us
went into finance.

00:58:21.280 --> 00:58:24.700
So this is really now we're
talking about the early '80s.

00:58:24.700 --> 00:58:28.230
The people who
like casino games,

00:58:28.230 --> 00:58:30.447
they like secretive
little hedge funds.

00:58:30.447 --> 00:58:32.030
They wanted to invest
their own money.

00:58:32.030 --> 00:58:34.254
There are only a few
wealthy investors.

00:58:34.254 --> 00:58:35.670
As soon as they
could, they wanted

00:58:35.670 --> 00:58:39.100
to pay off their investors
and just be by themselves.

00:58:39.100 --> 00:58:43.070
And some of this really
brilliant stuff [INAUDIBLE]

00:58:43.070 --> 00:58:44.170
fairly narrow focused.

00:58:44.170 --> 00:58:46.460
They had to like pick some
narrow niche kind of thing

00:58:46.460 --> 00:58:48.840
and do it.

00:58:48.840 --> 00:58:50.580
Bayesians, these
people were naturals.

00:58:50.580 --> 00:58:52.280
These people went
into big bank stuff.

00:58:52.280 --> 00:58:53.150
They knew people.

00:58:53.150 --> 00:58:54.160
They knew businesses.

00:58:54.160 --> 00:58:58.530
They were bank executive types.

00:58:58.530 --> 00:59:01.019
And by the way, in these
days I'm talking about,

00:59:01.019 --> 00:59:02.810
you left math off your
resume if you wanted

00:59:02.810 --> 00:59:05.090
to apply for a Wall Street job.

00:59:05.090 --> 00:59:06.079
I'm not kidding.

00:59:06.079 --> 00:59:07.620
People thought if
you knew math, it'd

00:59:07.620 --> 00:59:09.727
be like you want
to go to the NFL.

00:59:09.727 --> 00:59:11.310
You know, the NFL,
they don't want you

00:59:11.310 --> 00:59:12.520
if you've got a PhD in math.

00:59:12.520 --> 00:59:15.030
It's like they don't
want smart people.

00:59:15.030 --> 00:59:18.000
Wall Street did not want
people who knew math.

00:59:18.000 --> 00:59:20.120
Some of them understood
that smart people

00:59:20.120 --> 00:59:21.460
would be dangerous.

00:59:21.460 --> 00:59:25.190
Others just thought that anybody
in math had to be ivory tower

00:59:25.190 --> 00:59:28.520
and couldn't possibly
know anything.

00:59:28.520 --> 00:59:30.730
But still, once you
got there, these skills

00:59:30.730 --> 00:59:32.040
were incredibly useful.

00:59:32.040 --> 00:59:36.570
If you'd been five, six years
betting sports successfully,

00:59:36.570 --> 00:59:39.180
you know a lot of stuff
about markets and businesses

00:59:39.180 --> 00:59:41.140
and how to run
things with people

00:59:41.140 --> 00:59:43.160
that some of these
other people would never

00:59:43.160 --> 00:59:45.760
learn their whole lives.

00:59:45.760 --> 00:59:49.390
These people didn't have to get
a job, but they're problem was,

00:59:49.390 --> 00:59:51.050
could they find
somebody to trade with?

00:59:51.050 --> 00:59:53.560
Could they get people
to broker for them,

00:59:53.560 --> 00:59:54.930
to trade with them, and so on?

00:59:54.930 --> 00:59:57.870
So they had a lot
problems with that.

00:59:57.870 --> 01:00:01.930
Me, poker players, people
like me, we could get jobs.

01:00:01.930 --> 01:00:04.500
We didn't want high level
executive jobs though.

01:00:04.500 --> 01:00:08.030
We wanted to run some little
department under the radar

01:00:08.030 --> 01:00:08.530
screen.

01:00:08.530 --> 01:00:10.220
We'd run a quant trading team.

01:00:10.220 --> 01:00:11.350
We do some pairs trading.

01:00:11.350 --> 01:00:12.860
We do some quant stuff.

01:00:12.860 --> 01:00:14.440
We do structured products.

01:00:14.440 --> 01:00:16.730
We did a lot of
that kind of stuff.

01:00:16.730 --> 01:00:20.150
We were used to networking--
we were good at that--

01:00:20.150 --> 01:00:21.320
but under the screen.

01:00:21.320 --> 01:00:24.750
We weren't good at like
showing up in a suit and tie

01:00:24.750 --> 01:00:27.190
and being nice to bosses
and things like that.

01:00:27.190 --> 01:00:29.270
We weren't good
at raising money,

01:00:29.270 --> 01:00:33.200
which is why we had to go
hook up with a big firm.

01:00:33.200 --> 01:00:36.330
We liked the fact that a firm
would give us trading capital,

01:00:36.330 --> 01:00:39.010
the firm would give us
setup relationships,

01:00:39.010 --> 01:00:41.260
so we didn't have any problem
opening up trading lines

01:00:41.260 --> 01:00:42.135
and things like that.

01:00:44.840 --> 01:00:46.800
But we basically got
to keep what we made,

01:00:46.800 --> 01:00:49.530
or we got to keep a
portion of what we made,

01:00:49.530 --> 01:00:52.680
which is a way we like to do it.

01:00:52.680 --> 01:00:56.190
This is what really
revolutionized Wall Street.

01:00:56.190 --> 01:00:59.890
The thing I tell people is,
having lived through this

01:00:59.890 --> 01:01:02.900
from the early '80s
to now, it's people

01:01:02.900 --> 01:01:05.180
don't understand how
much finance has changed.

01:01:05.180 --> 01:01:06.840
An awful lot of
finance is written

01:01:06.840 --> 01:01:09.490
as if there's some
continuous history,

01:01:09.490 --> 01:01:11.520
some minor technical
innovations,

01:01:11.520 --> 01:01:15.120
electronic trading is just a
little bit faster way of people

01:01:15.120 --> 01:01:17.110
yelling at each other in a pit.

01:01:17.110 --> 01:01:18.190
Well, it's not true.

01:01:18.190 --> 01:01:21.170
The entire fundamental
technological basis of finance

01:01:21.170 --> 01:01:24.760
has changed, has
completely been redone.

01:01:24.760 --> 01:01:28.530
I use the analogy of a digital
camera versus a chemical

01:01:28.530 --> 01:01:29.824
camera.

01:01:29.824 --> 01:01:31.740
They kind of look the
same-- or they used, now

01:01:31.740 --> 01:01:32.656
they're in your phone.

01:01:32.656 --> 01:01:35.895
But a few years ago, a digital
camera looked kind of the same.

01:01:35.895 --> 01:01:36.822
It runs on battery.

01:01:36.822 --> 01:01:37.530
It's got a flash.

01:01:37.530 --> 01:01:38.390
It's got a lens.

01:01:38.390 --> 01:01:40.456
It's got a shutter button.

01:01:40.456 --> 01:01:41.830
People use it for
the same thing.

01:01:41.830 --> 01:01:44.038
They take pictures of their
friends, their vacations,

01:01:44.038 --> 01:01:46.170
their parties, things like that.

01:01:46.170 --> 01:01:49.170
But the technology inside is
entirely, totally different.

01:01:49.170 --> 01:01:51.485
If you want to
make a camera, you

01:01:51.485 --> 01:01:52.860
hire completely
different people,

01:01:52.860 --> 01:01:54.270
use completely
different processes,

01:01:54.270 --> 01:01:55.750
the theory is
completely different.

01:01:55.750 --> 01:01:57.510
Well, that's the
difference in finance.

01:01:57.510 --> 01:02:00.435
And the people of my generation,
the quants in my generation,

01:02:00.435 --> 01:02:02.120
are the ones that built that.

01:02:02.120 --> 01:02:04.490
And most of it has a
lot more of its genetics

01:02:04.490 --> 01:02:08.010
come from sports betting and
betting casino games and poker

01:02:08.010 --> 01:02:12.680
than it does from economic
theory of the 1970s and 1980s

01:02:12.680 --> 01:02:13.230
era vintage.

01:02:15.417 --> 01:02:17.500
For those of you who are
interested in this stuff,

01:02:17.500 --> 01:02:19.750
I put a few books here.

01:02:19.750 --> 01:02:21.607
I did these in alphabetical
order of title.

01:02:21.607 --> 01:02:23.190
I do have couple of
my own books here,

01:02:23.190 --> 01:02:26.420
but Beat the Market
by Ed Thorpe.

01:02:26.420 --> 01:02:28.140
Just read anything
you can by Ed Thorpe.

01:02:28.140 --> 01:02:31.339
A lot of it's
available free online.

01:02:31.339 --> 01:02:32.130
You've just got to.

01:02:34.710 --> 01:02:38.790
That's a guy who
understands stuff.

01:02:38.790 --> 01:02:42.330
James McManus, a friend of
mine, wrote Cowboys Full.

01:02:42.330 --> 01:02:44.200
Some of you may remember James.

01:02:44.200 --> 01:02:46.460
He made the final table at
the main event of the World

01:02:46.460 --> 01:02:49.070
Series of Poker and wrote a
best selling book about it,

01:02:49.070 --> 01:02:52.260
which is a lot of fun,
too-- Positively 5th Street.

01:02:52.260 --> 01:02:54.087
But this is a history
of poker if that's

01:02:54.087 --> 01:02:55.170
what you're interested in.

01:02:55.170 --> 01:02:58.882
It's really the only
good history of poker.

01:02:58.882 --> 01:03:01.215
This is a really interesting
book, The Economic Function

01:03:01.215 --> 01:03:03.120
of Futures Markets.

01:03:03.120 --> 01:03:06.520
For about 100 years, people
wrote nothing but nonsense

01:03:06.520 --> 01:03:08.200
about futures markets.

01:03:08.200 --> 01:03:10.100
And then this guy came along.

01:03:10.100 --> 01:03:14.460
He had a PhD, came along, and
wrote a thin book about 1990

01:03:14.460 --> 01:03:16.290
that absolutely explained it.

01:03:16.290 --> 01:03:18.740
And it's funny, because
after reading nonsense-- just

01:03:18.740 --> 01:03:21.694
transparent nonsense about
futures markets all the time--

01:03:21.694 --> 01:03:22.610
this guy wrote a book.

01:03:22.610 --> 01:03:24.980
And the thing about this
book is it's logical.

01:03:24.980 --> 01:03:25.630
It makes sense.

01:03:25.630 --> 01:03:26.590
He's got a story.

01:03:26.590 --> 01:03:27.332
It makes sense.

01:03:27.332 --> 01:03:28.790
He's got empirical
evidence for it.

01:03:28.790 --> 01:03:29.570
He nailed it.

01:03:29.570 --> 01:03:32.102
He explained what
futures markets are.

01:03:32.102 --> 01:03:33.560
And nobody ever
paid any attention.

01:03:33.560 --> 01:03:34.410
I mean, nobody ever cites it.

01:03:34.410 --> 01:03:35.330
Nobody ever reads it.

01:03:35.330 --> 01:03:35.780
Whatever.

01:03:35.780 --> 01:03:37.446
But if you want to
know futures markets,

01:03:37.446 --> 01:03:40.600
this is the guy who explains it.

01:03:40.600 --> 01:03:43.430
Fischer Black-- by the
way, this is the hardback

01:03:43.430 --> 01:03:44.600
which has a blue cover.

01:03:44.600 --> 01:03:46.670
If you buy the paperback
with a black cover,

01:03:46.670 --> 01:03:48.510
it has a foreward by me.

01:03:48.510 --> 01:03:51.430
So I go for the paperback.

01:03:51.430 --> 01:03:54.459
But this is really interesting.

01:03:54.459 --> 01:03:56.000
If you're interested
in the time when

01:03:56.000 --> 01:03:57.737
I was at Harvard and
hanging around MIT

01:03:57.737 --> 01:03:59.320
and talking to people
who were arguing

01:03:59.320 --> 01:04:01.000
about this kind of
stuff, Fischer Black

01:04:01.000 --> 01:04:03.790
was a very important
part of that.

01:04:03.790 --> 01:04:06.450
I knew him pretty
well in those days.

01:04:06.450 --> 01:04:11.000
And there's a lot of really
interesting stuff about how

01:04:11.000 --> 01:04:13.200
logic and rationality
and mathematics actually

01:04:13.200 --> 01:04:16.030
came into finance.

01:04:16.030 --> 01:04:17.420
It didn't come in naturally.

01:04:17.420 --> 01:04:20.680
It was some eccentric thinkers--
Fischer Black was nothing if

01:04:20.680 --> 01:04:22.830
not eccentric-- who did it.

01:04:22.830 --> 01:04:24.950
And this book explains it.

01:04:24.950 --> 01:04:27.230
A guy by the name of Perry
Mehrling, Perry Mehrling's

01:04:27.230 --> 01:04:30.837
a nice guy who wrote another
good book, The New Lombard

01:04:30.837 --> 01:04:33.045
Street, that's very interesting
about modern finance.

01:04:35.970 --> 01:04:39.260
This is a book by Daniel
Usner, who I do not know.

01:04:39.260 --> 01:04:40.790
This kind of covers
the prehistory.

01:04:40.790 --> 01:04:42.510
This tells you
what the world was

01:04:42.510 --> 01:04:47.070
like in the Northwest United
States before poker came in.

01:04:47.070 --> 01:04:51.670
It goes up to, I
think, 1791 or so.

01:04:51.670 --> 01:04:53.370
So it's a pre-history.

01:04:53.370 --> 01:04:55.240
But it's really
fascinating economics.

01:04:55.240 --> 01:04:57.717
There was a really
fascinating economy

01:04:57.717 --> 01:04:58.800
in this part of the world.

01:04:58.800 --> 01:05:03.450
The pre-modern economy,
but it had within it more

01:05:03.450 --> 01:05:07.110
of the design of the modern
economy than if you'd

01:05:07.110 --> 01:05:10.380
gone to London or New
York at the same time.

01:05:10.380 --> 01:05:12.170
This is a book, another
guy I don't know.

01:05:12.170 --> 01:05:13.669
I actually talked
to him a few times

01:05:13.669 --> 01:05:15.495
about this book when
he was writing it,

01:05:15.495 --> 01:05:17.010
but this is More Money Than God.

01:05:17.010 --> 01:05:18.947
It's an excellent story
of the early hedge

01:05:18.947 --> 01:05:20.780
funds, a lot of these
people who were coming

01:05:20.780 --> 01:05:22.800
from these sorts of
backgrounds, bringing

01:05:22.800 --> 01:05:24.185
some mathematics into finance.

01:05:26.755 --> 01:05:28.390
It doesn't have a
tremendous insight.

01:05:28.390 --> 01:05:30.490
He doesn't get
into the strategies

01:05:30.490 --> 01:05:32.750
or the intellectual
ideas behind the things,

01:05:32.750 --> 01:05:34.690
but he'll tell you the
stories of the people

01:05:34.690 --> 01:05:37.890
and what happened
and stuff like that.

01:05:37.890 --> 01:05:39.790
Two books that I--
I sort of did this

01:05:39.790 --> 01:05:42.550
as I was coming up with this
and I just pulled up some books.

01:05:42.550 --> 01:05:44.039
But there are two
that I left off

01:05:44.039 --> 01:05:45.580
that I was thinking
on the train ride

01:05:45.580 --> 01:05:47.240
up I should have put on here.

01:05:47.240 --> 01:05:48.745
One of them is
called Poker Faces

01:05:48.745 --> 01:05:52.510
by a guy named David Hayano.

01:05:52.510 --> 01:05:54.560
He's another guy,
knew him in Gardena.

01:05:54.560 --> 01:05:56.720
He was a player in Gardena.

01:05:56.720 --> 01:05:59.750
He was also working on
his PhD in sociology.

01:05:59.750 --> 01:06:05.040
Actually, he called himself
an autoethnographer.

01:06:05.040 --> 01:06:11.639
So he was an ethnographer
who studied himself.

01:06:11.639 --> 01:06:12.180
And he wrote.

01:06:12.180 --> 01:06:14.554
Anyway, he wrote he wrote a
book on Gardena and the poker

01:06:14.554 --> 01:06:15.940
economy and what it was like.

01:06:15.940 --> 01:06:17.567
I'm actually in the book.

01:06:17.567 --> 01:06:19.400
But it really is a great
book, and it really

01:06:19.400 --> 01:06:22.190
tells you kind of what the poker
economy was like in the '70s.

01:06:22.190 --> 01:06:27.090
I think that was the last
gasp that takes us back.

01:06:27.090 --> 01:06:31.530
It was a lot weaker than it
was in the 1840s Chicago.

01:06:31.530 --> 01:06:34.140
So it wasn't as
important to the economy,

01:06:34.140 --> 01:06:35.670
but it was still there.

01:06:35.670 --> 01:06:39.720
You could really see a lot
of the relations, how things

01:06:39.720 --> 01:06:41.187
worked, really were there.

01:06:41.187 --> 01:06:42.520
I think that's kind of gone now.

01:06:42.520 --> 01:06:44.890
You really don't
find that today.

01:06:44.890 --> 01:06:47.610
Another one is by a guy, a
friend of mine, professor Phil

01:06:47.610 --> 01:06:49.500
Tetlock lock at Wharton.

01:06:49.500 --> 01:06:53.240
He wrote a book called
Expert Political Judgment.

01:06:53.240 --> 01:06:54.790
And that tells you
a lot about what

01:06:54.790 --> 01:06:57.630
the things that drove
me away from basically

01:06:57.630 --> 01:07:00.240
how bad experts are
predicting stuff.

01:07:00.240 --> 01:07:02.124
And what really drives
you to-- if you're

01:07:02.124 --> 01:07:04.540
good at this tough stuff, if
you're a quantitative person,

01:07:04.540 --> 01:07:07.660
if you like to make bets, if
you like to back your judgment,

01:07:07.660 --> 01:07:09.510
you've just got to
stay away from experts.

01:07:09.510 --> 01:07:12.220
You've got to go someplace where
you find out in cold, hard cash

01:07:12.220 --> 01:07:15.700
whether you're making
good or bad predictions.

01:07:15.700 --> 01:07:17.800
Pokerface of Wall
Street, this is by me.

01:07:17.800 --> 01:07:21.060
This covers a lot of
stuff I'm talking about,

01:07:21.060 --> 01:07:24.050
the connection between
poker and finance.

01:07:24.050 --> 01:07:26.990
And Red Blooded
Risk, also by me,

01:07:26.990 --> 01:07:29.870
this tells a lot more about
how people brought ideas

01:07:29.870 --> 01:07:37.380
from sports betting and
poker and Casino games

01:07:37.380 --> 01:07:43.390
and how that entered
into mainstream finance.

01:07:43.390 --> 01:07:46.250
OK, that's what I've got.

01:07:46.250 --> 01:07:48.651
Any questions, comments?

01:07:48.651 --> 01:07:49.150
Yeah?

01:07:49.150 --> 01:07:54.870
AUDIENCE: How good was George
Bush and Bill Gates at Poker?

01:07:54.870 --> 01:07:57.565
PROFESSOR: I can't really
answer that in the sense that--

01:07:57.565 --> 01:07:58.940
to really answer
that, you'd have

01:07:58.940 --> 01:08:00.870
to like tracked their
winnings and losing

01:08:00.870 --> 01:08:02.180
for long periods of time.

01:08:02.180 --> 01:08:04.640
Bill ran a game
in Courier House.

01:08:04.640 --> 01:08:06.100
I didn't like the game.

01:08:06.100 --> 01:08:09.420
It was a very tense game.

01:08:09.420 --> 01:08:13.330
I always got the feeling people
lost more than they wanted to

01:08:13.330 --> 01:08:15.680
and it wasn't a
lot of fun to play.

01:08:15.680 --> 01:08:20.226
He was certainly a respectable
player at the time.

01:08:20.226 --> 01:08:21.850
You also have to
understand, I'm coming

01:08:21.850 --> 01:08:23.020
from a slightly
different perspective.

01:08:23.020 --> 01:08:24.700
I'm really at this
point one of the best

01:08:24.700 --> 01:08:26.145
players in the country.

01:08:26.145 --> 01:08:27.811
We didn't really have
ranking back then,

01:08:27.811 --> 01:08:29.149
it was kind of hard to tell.

01:08:29.149 --> 01:08:31.800
But I would say there were
maybe 100 people in the country

01:08:31.800 --> 01:08:33.675
that I would have felt
more or less equal to,

01:08:33.675 --> 01:08:34.970
and I wasn't afraid of anybody.

01:08:34.970 --> 01:08:36.260
I would sit down at
the table with anybody

01:08:36.260 --> 01:08:37.609
and play them kind of even.

01:08:37.609 --> 01:08:39.729
So none of these people
where that level.

01:08:39.729 --> 01:08:41.180
None of these
people were kind of

01:08:41.180 --> 01:08:43.510
serious, professional players.

01:08:43.510 --> 01:08:50.779
But in somebody can be a very
competent, careful player.

01:08:50.779 --> 01:08:52.529
George Bush was a lot
of fun to play with.

01:08:55.700 --> 01:08:57.359
Ran a great game.

01:08:57.359 --> 01:08:59.979
I don't think he was too
interested in the money.

01:08:59.979 --> 01:09:00.700
I'm not sure.

01:09:00.700 --> 01:09:01.840
He didn't seem to be.

01:09:05.050 --> 01:09:07.390
Probably more interested in
the connections, by the way.

01:09:07.390 --> 01:09:08.569
By the way, that
drove a lot of people.

01:09:08.569 --> 01:09:10.849
A lot of people-- I'm
talking about this networking

01:09:10.849 --> 01:09:12.130
in kind of this abstract.

01:09:12.130 --> 01:09:13.510
See, I'm an introvert.

01:09:13.510 --> 01:09:16.222
So for me, it's kind
of this amazing thing

01:09:16.222 --> 01:09:17.680
that you can create
these networks.

01:09:17.680 --> 01:09:19.263
I'm thinking of them
very mathematical

01:09:19.263 --> 01:09:20.729
and have a diagram.

01:09:20.729 --> 01:09:22.740
A lot of people are
just wired that way.

01:09:22.740 --> 01:09:25.412
They understand on some--
they don't sit down and draw

01:09:25.412 --> 01:09:26.120
network diagrams.

01:09:26.120 --> 01:09:27.399
They say, I'm going
to play in this game.

01:09:27.399 --> 01:09:28.229
I'm going to make some friends.

01:09:28.229 --> 01:09:29.450
I'm going to chat
with my friends.

01:09:29.450 --> 01:09:30.930
I'm going to buy
a baseball team.

01:09:30.930 --> 01:09:32.569
I'm going to be
president, whatever.

01:09:32.569 --> 01:09:34.374
It works for them.

01:09:34.374 --> 01:09:35.790
And that stuff
never works for me.

01:09:35.790 --> 01:09:36.831
I have to think about it.

01:09:36.831 --> 01:09:40.310
I have to do this on
an intellectual level.

01:09:40.310 --> 01:09:42.439
[INAUDIBLE] I would say
of the people I played

01:09:42.439 --> 01:09:47.060
at Harvard at that time,
the two that were probably

01:09:47.060 --> 01:09:50.990
the best in my recollection were
Scott Turow, the author, who

01:09:50.990 --> 01:09:54.790
was really could have
been a pro level player.

01:09:54.790 --> 01:09:59.310
Probably didn't play enough to
do it, but had the instincts,

01:09:59.310 --> 01:10:01.820
had the people skills and so on.

01:10:01.820 --> 01:10:04.690
And a guy named Lloyd Trefethen
who's a mathematician at Oxford

01:10:04.690 --> 01:10:07.800
now and just was a
really good-- actually

01:10:07.800 --> 01:10:09.220
taught me a lot of theory.

01:10:09.220 --> 01:10:11.000
We talked about
that stuff a lot.

01:10:15.030 --> 01:10:18.400
But all this, one thing I
will say in terms of that.

01:10:18.400 --> 01:10:20.740
The people at Garden,
the people at Gardena

01:10:20.740 --> 01:10:23.930
really were a cut above that.

01:10:23.930 --> 01:10:26.460
A pretty good club player
at Gardena, somebody

01:10:26.460 --> 01:10:28.690
who just kind of was
playing at the top stakes

01:10:28.690 --> 01:10:32.380
and breaking even, somebody
like that was so much

01:10:32.380 --> 01:10:35.330
better than the leather
ass Texas road gamblers

01:10:35.330 --> 01:10:37.916
who were playing off in
the World Series of Poker

01:10:37.916 --> 01:10:38.790
and things like that.

01:10:38.790 --> 01:10:40.350
You went to Las Vegas,
and these people just

01:10:40.350 --> 01:10:41.630
were not very good at poker.

01:10:41.630 --> 01:10:44.220
Now, they were very
good at making money

01:10:44.220 --> 01:10:46.640
at poker, which is a
little bit different.

01:10:46.640 --> 01:10:49.510
But if you just sat down, if you
just listened to the analysis

01:10:49.510 --> 01:10:51.880
they gave for why they
did things when they did,

01:10:51.880 --> 01:10:56.790
it was just-- they
believed in luck.

01:10:56.790 --> 01:10:59.370
They would make these
arguments that just

01:10:59.370 --> 01:11:01.870
made no strategic sense at all.

01:11:01.870 --> 01:11:04.110
They weren't even thinking
in terms of what you think

01:11:04.110 --> 01:11:07.150
of [? as ?] [? poker. ?] Now,
that had very little to do with

01:11:07.150 --> 01:11:10.260
making a living at poker.

01:11:10.260 --> 01:11:14.630
One of the stories I like
to tell is there's a story

01:11:14.630 --> 01:11:16.700
that's-- I read it
in a book, actually.

01:11:16.700 --> 01:11:18.700
I didn't know this at
the time, but three

01:11:18.700 --> 01:11:21.770
WSOP winners-- It
might have been

01:11:21.770 --> 01:11:23.250
Dolly Brunsen, Sailor Roberts.

01:11:23.250 --> 01:11:26.150
Sailor Roberts
was a good player.

01:11:26.150 --> 01:11:29.280
He was probably the only one in
that crowd that was really top.

01:11:29.280 --> 01:11:32.070
And one other, they used
to drive around Texas

01:11:32.070 --> 01:11:34.410
and play in just
local [INAUDIBLE].

01:11:34.410 --> 01:11:38.100
OK, 3 WSOP winners playing
in these Texas games

01:11:38.100 --> 01:11:40.830
and stuff, just local people.

01:11:40.830 --> 01:11:43.240
They should clean up, or they
should make tons of money.

01:11:43.240 --> 01:11:45.234
Sailor told me they broke even.

01:11:45.234 --> 01:11:47.400
They just weren't really
making money playing poker.

01:11:47.400 --> 01:11:49.860
What they were
doing was they were

01:11:49.860 --> 01:11:52.284
bag men for betting on
high school football.

01:11:52.284 --> 01:11:53.700
So they were going
to these towns,

01:11:53.700 --> 01:11:54.900
they were playing some poker.

01:11:54.900 --> 01:11:56.483
And then they were
collecting the bets

01:11:56.483 --> 01:11:58.460
and moving around and
getting paid for that.

01:11:58.460 --> 01:12:00.960
But the poker was a break
even operation for them.

01:12:00.960 --> 01:12:03.860
So a lot of people who have
great reputations in the poker

01:12:03.860 --> 01:12:08.275
place, lots of colorful stories,
and just you set them down

01:12:08.275 --> 01:12:11.220
at a computer, you set them down
at a tournament or something,

01:12:11.220 --> 01:12:15.940
they would just be
toast in five minutes.

01:12:15.940 --> 01:12:19.130
But the people, the
people in Gardena--

01:12:19.130 --> 01:12:21.857
who were much better in
terms of theoretical poker

01:12:21.857 --> 01:12:24.065
playing and playing the
game-- we would've been toast

01:12:24.065 --> 01:12:25.380
in that tavern in Texas, right?

01:12:25.380 --> 01:12:27.588
We would've been beaten over
the head with a pool cue

01:12:27.588 --> 01:12:30.432
and left out with the
cows or something.

01:12:30.432 --> 01:12:31.890
I don't just mean
we weren't tough.

01:12:31.890 --> 01:12:32.900
We weren't tough.

01:12:32.900 --> 01:12:34.390
We aren't tough.

01:12:34.390 --> 01:12:35.860
We didn't have social skills.

01:12:35.860 --> 01:12:37.790
We had just enough
social skills,

01:12:37.790 --> 01:12:40.260
some of us-- most of them
didn't even have that.

01:12:40.260 --> 01:12:43.441
I was considered pretty social
because I could actually

01:12:43.441 --> 01:12:45.690
get a game together of normal
people and collect money

01:12:45.690 --> 01:12:46.200
and so on.

01:12:46.200 --> 01:12:47.970
Most of these people couldn't.

01:12:47.970 --> 01:12:50.710
They couldn't play
with normal people.

01:12:50.710 --> 01:12:56.890
And none of us had the kind of
skills that those people did.

01:12:56.890 --> 01:12:58.030
Other questions?

01:12:58.030 --> 01:12:58.530
Yeah?

01:12:58.530 --> 01:13:00.529
AUDIENCE: You think if
you're a good player,

01:13:00.529 --> 01:13:02.570
are you better off making
a big name for yourself

01:13:02.570 --> 01:13:04.814
or staying under the radar?

01:13:04.814 --> 01:13:06.480
PROFESSOR: That's
hard for me to answer,

01:13:06.480 --> 01:13:08.539
because I come from
a strong tradition

01:13:08.539 --> 01:13:09.580
of being under the radar.

01:13:09.580 --> 01:13:11.038
It was very hard
for me to come up.

01:13:11.038 --> 01:13:13.750
When I wrote this book,
this was my first public

01:13:13.750 --> 01:13:14.430
acknowledgement.

01:13:14.430 --> 01:13:15.930
I mean, people who
knew me knew I played.

01:13:15.930 --> 01:13:17.763
Including on Wall
Street-- you know, I mean,

01:13:17.763 --> 01:13:19.700
a lot of famous
people on Wall Street

01:13:19.700 --> 01:13:21.250
play and play with whatever.

01:13:21.250 --> 01:13:23.660
But to sort of
come out in print--

01:13:23.660 --> 01:13:25.110
and when I talk
to people, I said,

01:13:25.110 --> 01:13:27.110
I'm going to tell a story
about you in the book.

01:13:27.110 --> 01:13:28.820
And people who you
would think would

01:13:28.820 --> 01:13:31.790
have no problem being identified
as a poker player just

01:13:31.790 --> 01:13:34.590
would not let me do it.

01:13:34.590 --> 01:13:37.950
But that said, there's a
whole career out there.

01:13:37.950 --> 01:13:39.700
I don't know if it's
still true, but there

01:13:39.700 --> 01:13:42.790
are people who made fortunes
by being famous poker players.

01:13:42.790 --> 01:13:45.710
And the thing I always
kind of wanted to do,

01:13:45.710 --> 01:13:47.410
I never liked tournaments.

01:13:47.410 --> 01:13:48.760
I don't like casinos.

01:13:48.760 --> 01:13:51.304
I played them
sometimes, but I like

01:13:51.304 --> 01:13:52.470
playing when I want to play.

01:13:52.470 --> 01:13:54.011
I don't like being
told when to play,

01:13:54.011 --> 01:13:56.490
and some of these
casinos, the experience

01:13:56.490 --> 01:13:58.940
is just so physically
unpleasant,

01:13:58.940 --> 01:14:01.220
playing at 2:00 in the
morning and getting bad chairs

01:14:01.220 --> 01:14:01.750
or whatever.

01:14:01.750 --> 01:14:07.050
But I was tempted by
high stakes poker.

01:14:07.050 --> 01:14:10.585
And I always thought that would
be kind of fun to go in there

01:14:10.585 --> 01:14:12.710
and play for cash and be
on television and do that.

01:14:12.710 --> 01:14:16.454
That was one that I
kind of thought of.

01:14:16.454 --> 01:14:20.480
But you also have to think
a little bit-- like I say,

01:14:20.480 --> 01:14:23.450
people in AQR have no problem
with me writing the books

01:14:23.450 --> 01:14:25.295
and giving talks
like this and so on.

01:14:25.295 --> 01:14:27.670
I don't know about me being
actually in poker after that.

01:14:27.670 --> 01:14:31.920
That probably would
be a step too much.

01:14:31.920 --> 01:14:34.990
So I think it's a choice
you make, who you are.

01:14:34.990 --> 01:14:37.690
And I think if you decide who
you are and you're true to it,

01:14:37.690 --> 01:14:39.530
you can be successful.

01:14:39.530 --> 01:14:41.364
What you don't want to
do is put on a front.

01:14:41.364 --> 01:14:43.280
If you put on a front
for something like that,

01:14:43.280 --> 01:14:44.850
it can come back to haunt you.

01:14:44.850 --> 01:14:48.070
So if you are a celebrity--
I'm just not a celebrity.

01:14:48.070 --> 01:14:48.810
I never could be.

01:14:48.810 --> 01:14:50.310
I'd never be happy being one.

01:14:50.310 --> 01:14:54.009
Nobody's offered to make
me one, but-- and it

01:14:54.009 --> 01:14:55.050
wouldn't be right for me.

01:14:55.050 --> 01:14:57.990
But if you are cut from that
cloth, you should do it.

01:14:57.990 --> 01:15:00.370
Be true to yourself.

01:15:00.370 --> 01:15:00.870
Yeah?

01:15:00.870 --> 01:15:03.036
AUDIENCE: How do you feel
the view of mathematicians

01:15:03.036 --> 01:15:08.399
on Wall Street has
changed since [INAUDIBLE]

01:15:08.399 --> 01:15:09.940
PROFESSOR: Sorry,
perception of what?

01:15:09.940 --> 01:15:12.720
AUDIENCE: Of mathematicians.

01:15:12.720 --> 01:15:15.100
PROFESSOR: It's gone through--
it kind of goes through.

01:15:15.100 --> 01:15:19.190
OK, so first, it
was just laughable.

01:15:19.190 --> 01:15:21.860
And let me explain how Wall
Street works, by the way.

01:15:21.860 --> 01:15:22.910
Wall Street is sales.

01:15:22.910 --> 01:15:23.810
Finance is sales.

01:15:23.810 --> 01:15:26.890
All the money in finance always
has, always will be in sales.

01:15:26.890 --> 01:15:28.530
A few quants can make
a couple of bucks

01:15:28.530 --> 01:15:30.950
on the edges-- a
few billion, even--

01:15:30.950 --> 01:15:33.270
but it's just not a lot in
the whole scheme of things.

01:15:33.270 --> 01:15:36.710
If you can bring money in,
if you can gather assets,

01:15:36.710 --> 01:15:39.050
it's always been rewarded.

01:15:39.050 --> 01:15:42.370
So when the early quants
came, the attitude is,

01:15:42.370 --> 01:15:46.490
let's say you're
like LOR associate.

01:15:46.490 --> 01:15:52.932
People [? know ?] [? that. ?]
O'Brian, Rubinstein,

01:15:52.932 --> 01:15:53.640
and I'm blanking.

01:15:53.640 --> 01:15:55.070
These are the people who
did portfolio insurance

01:15:55.070 --> 01:15:56.040
in the '80s, whatever.

01:15:56.040 --> 01:15:58.030
Anyway, so these finance
professors show up,

01:15:58.030 --> 01:15:59.377
these quants show up.

01:15:59.377 --> 01:16:00.960
What Wall Street is
saying, hey great.

01:16:00.960 --> 01:16:01.915
We don't care.

01:16:01.915 --> 01:16:03.190
You could astrologers.

01:16:03.190 --> 01:16:06.080
You could be
chartists, whatever.

01:16:06.080 --> 01:16:08.289
If you're gathering assets
and you're giving it to us

01:16:08.289 --> 01:16:09.830
and paying us
commissions to trade it

01:16:09.830 --> 01:16:12.390
back and forth, if you're
giving people reason to trade,

01:16:12.390 --> 01:16:13.835
we're happy to service you.

01:16:13.835 --> 01:16:15.120
And we'll pretend we
like you, and we'll

01:16:15.120 --> 01:16:16.120
pretend to respect you.

01:16:16.120 --> 01:16:17.274
Whatever, we don't care.

01:16:17.274 --> 01:16:18.190
And they really don't.

01:16:18.190 --> 01:16:20.990
And so that was kind of the
attitude toward mathematicians.

01:16:20.990 --> 01:16:22.860
If you have a way
to generate trades

01:16:22.860 --> 01:16:25.390
and to talk people into
trading, great, because we're

01:16:25.390 --> 01:16:26.690
just taking a commission.

01:16:26.690 --> 01:16:29.273
All we care about is that people
are coming in and doing this.

01:16:31.251 --> 01:16:33.375
Then they started figuring
out that, you know, hey,

01:16:33.375 --> 01:16:33.958
wait a minute.

01:16:33.958 --> 01:16:35.890
These guys aren't
like everybody else.

01:16:35.890 --> 01:16:38.390
These guys actually
are making money.

01:16:38.390 --> 01:16:40.620
Some of this stuff
really does make money.

01:16:40.620 --> 01:16:43.630
That's very, very
difficult for Wall Street

01:16:43.630 --> 01:16:45.160
to come to terms with.

01:16:45.160 --> 01:16:47.540
There's a New York
Times Magazine article

01:16:47.540 --> 01:16:51.760
about Lehman Brothers with Lou
Gluckman and Peter Peterson,

01:16:51.760 --> 01:16:54.880
the clash of those cultures--
the shirt sleeve, cigar

01:16:54.880 --> 01:16:59.940
chomping trader culture, totally
at odds with the white shoe

01:16:59.940 --> 01:17:03.020
investment banking culture
when these two things crashed.

01:17:03.020 --> 01:17:05.920
So then people were kind of
afraid of mathematicians,

01:17:05.920 --> 01:17:08.930
but also somewhat
dismissive of them.

01:17:08.930 --> 01:17:17.110
So then I think it's kind of
mellowed out a little bit.

01:17:17.110 --> 01:17:20.330
But I will still say, AQR
is a quant hedge fund.

01:17:20.330 --> 01:17:25.450
When we go and do
our credit thing,

01:17:25.450 --> 01:17:29.280
the credit counterparties,
the assumption

01:17:29.280 --> 01:17:31.975
is nobody can understand
your black box trading.

01:17:31.975 --> 01:17:33.087
Now, that's just not true.

01:17:33.087 --> 01:17:34.420
I mean, we are very transparent.

01:17:34.420 --> 01:17:35.211
We can sit it down.

01:17:35.211 --> 01:17:38.110
And certainly any of you could
figure it out in five minutes,

01:17:38.110 --> 01:17:40.292
but other people would
maybe take an hour.

01:17:40.292 --> 01:17:41.250
But we can lay it down.

01:17:41.250 --> 01:17:42.410
Here's what we do.

01:17:42.410 --> 01:17:44.830
Here are the eight signals
and we measure these things.

01:17:44.830 --> 01:17:47.210
And we add them up
and we find the best

01:17:47.210 --> 01:17:49.590
and we buy this
and we short that.

01:17:49.590 --> 01:17:53.220
It's a lot simpler than
somebody who's saying,

01:17:53.220 --> 01:17:56.100
oh, I'm doing this quantitative
analysis or technical analysis

01:17:56.100 --> 01:17:58.451
or fundamental stuff and I'm
thinking about all these 80

01:17:58.451 --> 01:17:58.950
factors.

01:17:58.950 --> 01:18:02.220
We tell you exactly what we do.

01:18:02.220 --> 01:18:05.144
And they always assign the most
junior credit person to us,

01:18:05.144 --> 01:18:07.310
because they figure nobody
can understand it anyway,

01:18:07.310 --> 01:18:10.550
so why waste somebody who
knows what's going on?

01:18:10.550 --> 01:18:14.650
That kind of prejudice you
still find a lot, that somehow

01:18:14.650 --> 01:18:16.370
what we do is crazy.

01:18:16.370 --> 01:18:17.597
It's a little weird.

01:18:17.597 --> 01:18:18.930
Nobody can really understand it.

01:18:18.930 --> 01:18:21.517
It seems to kind of work, so
we'll continue to do business.

01:18:21.517 --> 01:18:22.350
We'll recommend you.

01:18:22.350 --> 01:18:24.570
We'll put our client's
money in you, but not

01:18:24.570 --> 01:18:28.290
with the same confidence we
have with a guy who's saying,

01:18:28.290 --> 01:18:31.160
I went to the company
and I pounded the tires

01:18:31.160 --> 01:18:34.150
and I talked to the CEO
and I shook him and said,

01:18:34.150 --> 01:18:35.810
tell me what's
really going on here.

01:18:35.810 --> 01:18:38.320
And I understand this stuff.

01:18:38.320 --> 01:18:41.270
The biggest problem is
you're quant's not confident.

01:18:41.270 --> 01:18:47.024
It's still the case that people
measure your credibility,

01:18:47.024 --> 01:18:49.190
how much they believe you,
by how confident you are.

01:18:49.190 --> 01:18:51.290
So if I come in and say,
well, I got this model.

01:18:51.290 --> 01:18:52.498
It seems to work pretty well.

01:18:52.498 --> 01:18:55.250
I think I got a 60% chance that
this trade will make money.

01:18:55.250 --> 01:18:57.750
They just think you're-- they
don't know where you're coming

01:18:57.750 --> 01:18:58.820
from, what planet.

01:18:58.820 --> 01:19:01.153
A guy comes in and says, I'm
sure this is going to work.

01:19:01.153 --> 01:19:01.830
It's got to.

01:19:01.830 --> 01:19:03.930
I've got all these
87 reasons, whatever.

01:19:03.930 --> 01:19:05.220
Now, they don't believe them.

01:19:05.220 --> 01:19:07.300
They think it's 51% just like.

01:19:07.300 --> 01:19:09.390
But they expect
him to be confident

01:19:09.390 --> 01:19:10.967
and they understand that.

01:19:10.967 --> 01:19:12.550
So I think that's
the biggest problem.

01:19:12.550 --> 01:19:14.216
If you want to be a
quant and you really

01:19:14.216 --> 01:19:17.020
want to be honest about
your confidence for things,

01:19:17.020 --> 01:19:19.696
